 University Press|isbn=978-0801887918|editor=Sumit Ganguly |editor2=Larry Diamond |editor3=Marc F. Plattner|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ganguly|first=Sumit|title=The Kashmir Question: Retrospect and Prospect|year=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0714684390|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Human Rights Watch|first=H R.|title=Compounding Injustice: The Government's Failure to Redress Massacres in Gujarat|year=2003|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration internationale des droits de l'homme|page=57|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2003/06/30/compounding-injustice|ref= {{sfnref|Human Rights Watch|2003}} }}\n* {{cite news |last=Hazarika |first=Sanjoy |title=Peace fragile in Assam a year after carnage |newspaper=The New York Times |date=26 February 1984 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/02/26/world/peace-fragile-in-assam-a-year-after-carnage.html |accessdate=2015-04-08 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hefner|first=Robert W.|title=Schooling Islam: The Culture and Politics of Modern Muslim Education|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0691129334|editor=Robert W. Hefner |editor2=Muhammad Qasim Zaman|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Holt|first=Peter M.|title=The Cambridge History of Islam|year=1977|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521291378|edition=New|editor=Peter Malcolm Holt |editor2=Ann K. S. Lambton |editor3=Bernard Lewis|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Herman|first=Phyllis K.|title=Muslim Cultures Today: A Reference Guide|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood|isbn=978-0313323867|editor=Kathryn M. Coughlin|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/muslimculturesto0000unse}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hussain|first=Monirul|title=The Fleeing People of South Asia: Selections from Refugee Watch|date=1 February 2009|publisher=Anthem|isbn=978-8190583572|page=261|editor=Sibaji Pratim Basu|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Holst|first=Arthur|title=Encyclopedia of rape|date=30 August 2004|publisher=Greenwood|isbn=978-0313326875|editor=Merril D. Smith|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jaffrelot|first=Christophe|title=Religion, Caste, and Politics in India|year=2011|publisher=C Hurst & Co|isbn=978-1849041386|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jaffrelot|first=Christophe|title=The Hindu Nationalist Movement and Indian Politics 1925-1990s: Strategies of Identity-Building, Implantation and Mobilisation|year=1996|publisher=C Hurst & Co|isbn=9781850653011|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news|last=Krishnan|first=Murali|title=Modi's clearance in the Gujarat riots case angers Indian Muslims|url=http://www.dw.de/modis-clearance-in-the-gujarat-riots-case-angers-indian-muslims/a-15874606|newspaper=Deutsche Welle|date=11 March 2012|author2=Shamil Shams|ref= {{sfnref|Krishnan|2012}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Khalidi|first=Omar|title=Islam and democratization in Asia|date=28 December 2009|publisher=Cambria Press|isbn=978-1604976328|editor=Shiping Hua|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kaviraj|first=Sudipta|title=The Imaginary Institution of India: Politics and Ideas|year=2010|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0231152235|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kaur|first=Raminder|title=Performative Politics and the Cultures of Hinduism: Public Uses of Religion in Western India|date=5 February 2005|publisher=Anthem|isbn=978-1843311393|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Murphy|first=Eamon|title=Contemporary State Terrorism: Theory and Practice|date=24 March 2011|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415664479|editor=Richard Jackson |editor2=Eamon Murphy |editor3=Scott Poynting|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Markovits|first=Claude|title=India from 1900 to 1947|url=http://www.massviolence.org/India-from-1900-to-1947?cs=print#outil_sommaire_3|publisher=Mass Violence.Org|ref= {{sfnref|Markovits}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Metcalf|first=Barbara|title=Schooling Islam: The Culture and Politics of Modern Muslim Education|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0691129334|editor=Robert W. Hefner |editor2=Muhammad Qasim Zaman|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Metcalf|first=Barbara|title=Communalism and Globalization in South Asia and its Diaspora|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415857857|editor=Deana Heath |editor2=Chandana Mathur|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mazzarella|first=William|title=Censorium: Cinema and the Open Edge of Mass Publicity|year=2013|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0822353881|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Metcalf|first=Barbara D.|title=Islam in South Asia in Practice|year=2009|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0691044200|editor=Barbara D. Metcalf|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Price|first=Daniel E.|title=Sacred Terror: How Faith Becomes Lethal|year=2012|publisher=Praeger|isbn=978-0313386381|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Prakash|first=Gyan|title=The Crisis of Secularism in India|date=15 February 2007|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0822338468|editor=Anuradha Dingwaney Needham |editor2=Rajeswari Sunder Rajan|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Puniyan|first=Ram|title=Communal Politics: Facts Versus Myths|year=2003|publisher=Sage|isbn=978-0761996675|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pennington|first=Brian K.|title=Teaching Religion and Violence|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0195372427|editor=Brian K. Pennington|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/teachingreli_xxxx_2012_000_10891801}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pandey|first=Gyanendra|title=Routine violence: nations, fragments, histories|date=1 November 2005|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0804752640|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/routineviolencen0000pand}}\n* {{cite book|last=Risam|first=Roopika|title=Encyclopedia of Social Movement Media|date=30 December 2010|publisher=Sage|isbn=978-0761926887|editor=John D. H. Downing|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Raman|first=Sita Anantha|title=Women in India: a social and cultural history|date=8 June 2009|publisher=Praeger|isbn=978-0275982423|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Riddick|first=John F.|title=The History of British India: A Chronology|year=2006|publisher=Praeger|isbn=978-0313322808|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Riaz|first=Ali|authorlink=Ali Riaz|date=2008|title=Faithful Education: Madrassahs in South Asia|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0813543451|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news|last=Narula|first=Smita|title=India: Gujarat Officials Took Part in Anti-Muslim Violence|publisher=Human Rights Watch|date=1 May 2002|quote=not a spontaneous uprising, it was a carefully orchestrated attack against Muslims. The attacks were planned in advance and organised with extensive participation of the police and state government officials|ref= {{sfnref|Narula|2002}} }}\n* {{cite news |last1=Kokrajhar |last2=Dhubri |title=Killing for a homeland |newspaper=The Economist Banyan blog |date=24 August 2012 |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/08/ethnic-fissures-assam |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825124214/https://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/08/ethnic-fissures-assam |archive-date=25 August 2012 |url-access=subscription |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Saikia|first=Yasmin|title=Fragmented Memories: Struggling to be Tai-Ahom in India|year=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0822333739|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sarkur|first=Tanika|title=Women and the Politics of Violence|year=2007|publisher=Har Anand|isbn=978-8124108475|editor=Taisha Abraham|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shani|first=Giorgio|title=Sikh nationalism and identity in a global age|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415421904|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shani|first=Ornit|title=Communalism, Caste and Hindu Nationalism: The Violence in Gujarat|year=2007|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521727532|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sikand|first=Yoginder|title=The Blackwell Companion to Contemporary Islamic Thought|year=2006|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-1405121743|page=88|editor=Ibrahim Abu-Rabi'|quote=In the fascist Hindutva imagination, the Indian Muslims are continuously reviled as Pakistani \"fifth columnists,\" as \"enemies of the nation\" and so on, and their patriotism is said to be suspect. The Muslim as the menacing \"other\" occupies a central place in Hindutva discourse, and this has been used to legitimize large-scale anti-Muslim violence.|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sikand|first=Yoginder|title=Muslims in India Since 1947: Islamic Perspectives on Inter-Faith Relations|year=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415314862|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Singh |first=Sujala |chapter=Bombay Cinema: Terror and Spectacle |date=2010 |editor1-last=Boehmer  |editor1-first=Elleke |editor1-link=Elleke Boehmer |editor2-last=Morton |editor2-first=Stephen |title=Terror and the Postcolonial |location=Malden, MA |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |page=348 |isbn=978-1-4051-9154-8  |quote=one of the most horrific instances of fascistic state terror took place in Gujarat in 2002 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Singh|first=Ujjwal Kumar|title=Global Anti-Terrorism Law and Policy|year=2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107014671|page=427|edition=2nd|editor=Victor V. Ramraj |editor2=Michael Hor |editor3=Kent Roach|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Smith|first=Glenn|title=Violent Internal Conflicts in Asia Pacific: Histories, Political Economies, and Policies|year=2005|publisher=Yayasan Obor|isbn=9789794615140|editor=Asvi Warman Adam |editor2=Dewi Fortuna Anwar|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Swami|first=Praveen|title=India, Pakistan and the Secret Jihad: The Covert War in Kashmir, 1947\u20132004|date=19 October 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0415404594|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tilly|first=Charles|title=Regimes and Repertoires|year=2006|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0226803500|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tambiah|first=Stanely J.|title=Leveling Crowds: EthnoNationalist Conflicts and Collective Violence in South Asia|year=1997|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0520206427|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news|last=Times of India|first=TNN|title=State pogroms glossed over|newspaper=The Times of India|date=31 December 2005|ref= {{sfnref|Times of India|2005}} }}\n* {{cite news|last=Varia|first=Toral|title=Mumbai riots a planned, perfected pogrom?|newspaper=CNN-IBN|date=2 September 2007|ref= {{sfnref|Varia|2007}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Varshney|first=Ashutosh|title=Ethnic Conflict and Civic Life: Hindus and Muslims in India|year=2003|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300100136|page=8|edition=2nd Revised|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Vickery|first=Jacqueline|title=Encyclopedia of Social Movement Media|date=30 December 2010|publisher=Sage|isbn=978-0761926887|editor=John D. H. Downing|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Varshney|first=Ashutosh|title=Understanding Gujarat Violence|url=http://conconflicts.ssrc.org/archives/gujarat/varshney/|publisher=Social Science Research Council|ref= {{sfnref|Varshney}} }}\n* {{cite book|last=Weigl|first=Constanze|title=Reproductive Health Behaviour and Decision-making of Muslim Women: An Ethnographic Study in a Low-income Community in Urban North India|year=2012|publisher=Lit Verlag|isbn=978-3643107701|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wilkinson|first=Steven I.|title=Votes and Violence: Electoral Competition and Ethnic Riots in India|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521536059|ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|last=Brass|first=Paul R.|title=On the Study of Riots, Pogroms, and Genocide|url=http://faculty.washington.edu/brass/Ripogen.pdf|publisher=University of Washington}}\n{{Riots in India}}\n{{Discrimination}}\n{{Religious persecution}}\n\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims|India]]\n[[Category:Religious riots]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India| ]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n", "name_user": "2405:205:1588:314c::154c:70a0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added positive content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violence_against_Muslims_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Riverstone, New South Wales", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb\n| name     = Riverstone\n| city     = Sydney\n| state    = nsw\n| image    = Riverstonensw.JPG\n| image2   ={{maplink\n|frame=yes\n|frame-width=260\n|frame-height=280\n|frame-align=center\n|zoom=13\n|type=shape\n|stroke-colour=#C60C30\n|stroke-width=3\n}}\n| caption  = Riverstone Town Centre\n| lga      = [[City of Blacktown]], [[City of Hawkesbury]] \n| postcode = 2765\n| est      = \n| pop      = 7247\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=abs2016>{{Census 2016 AUS |id=SSC13368 |name=Riverstone (State Suburb) |accessdate=15 January 2018 |quick=on}}</ref>\n| area     = \n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Riverstone|Riverstone]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Greenway|Greenway]], [[Division of Chifley|Chifley]]\n| near-nw  = [[South Windsor, New South Wales|South Windsor]]\n| near-n   = [[Vineyard, New South Wales|Vineyard]]\n| near-ne  = [[Box Hill, New South Wales|Box Hill]]\n| near-w   = [[Windsor Downs, New South Wales|Windsor Downs]]\n| near-e   = [[Rouse Hill, New South Wales|Rouse Hill]]\n| near-sw  = [[Marsden Park, New South Wales|Marsden Park]]\n| near-s   = [[Schofields, New South Wales|Schofields]]\n| near-se  = [[Rouse Hill, New South Wales|Rouse Hill]]\n| dist1    = 48\n| dir1     = NW\n| location1= Sydney CBD \n}}\n'''Riverstone''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|r|a\u026a|v|'|a\u026a\u0259r|'|s|t|\u0252|n}}) ([[Postcodes in Australia|postcode]]: 2765) is a [[suburb]] of [[Sydney]], in the state of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].<ref>{{NSW GNR|id = ujwGwpqbKW|title = Riverstone|accessdate = 4 August 2013}}</ref>  Riverstone is located {{convert|48|km}} north-west of the [[Sydney central business district]], in the [[City of Blacktown|Blacktown]] and [[City of Hawkesbury|Hawkesbury]] [[Local government in Australia|local government areas]]; parts of the [[Greater Western Sydney]] region. Originally settled in 1803 as part of a government stock farm, Riverstone is one of the oldest towns in Australia.\n\nAs at the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]], Riverstone had an estimated population of 7,247.<ref name=abs2016/>\n\n==History==\nPrior to [[History of Australia (1788-1850)|settlement and colonisation]] of Australia, the area that was to become known as Riverstone was inhabited by the [[Darug people|Darug tribe]]. Most of these people died due to introduced diseases following the arrival of the [[First Fleet]], and the remainder were largely relocated to government farms and a series of settlements.\n\nThe Sydney Cove region originally settled in 1788 turned out to be unsuitable for farming, and after a number of years of near-famine in the colony, efforts were made to relocate food production inland to hopefully more climatically stable regions.  In 1803 a government stock farm was established in what was to become the Riverstone/Marsden Park area, on the basis of the abundant water supply and good grazing land there. In 1810 Lieut-Col [[Maurice Charles O'Connell]] was granted 2,500 acres (10&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land in the district, which he named \"Riverston Farm\", after his birthplace in Ireland. (The \"e\" at the end first appeared on railway timetables in the 1860s, an apparent  misprint that has become the accepted spelling, although the name is still pronounced as though the \"e\" is not present).\n\nOriginally, beef cattle farmed in the area were driven overland to the [[Hawkesbury River]] for transport by sailing ship to the convict settlement at [[Sydney Cove]]. The construction of the Sydney to Richmond Railway line in the 1864 both eliminated the need for this and opened up the region to non-rural development. \nAn important meatworks was established there in 1878, undergoing various stages of rebuilding and expansion until it closed permanently in 1992.\n\nIn 1970, a major fire at the Riverstone Meatworks killed six men, who were attempting to lead the animals to safety.\n\nIn 1988, as part of a Federal Government programme to commemorate the 200th anniversary of European settlement in Australia, a heritage museum was established in the old Masonic hall.\n\n== Heritage listings ==\nRiverstone has a number of heritage-listed sites, including:\n* Riverstone Parade: [[Riverstone railway station]]<ref name=nswshr-1237>{{cite NSW SHR|5012209|Riverstone Railway Station Group and Residence|hr=01237|fn=H08/00175/1, 10/06094|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n* West Parade: [[House]] \n\n* Railway Terrace: [[Riverstone Railway Station]]\n\n==Developments==\n[[Image:Riverstone terrace.jpg|thumb|Riverstone Terrace]]\n\nIn the 1880s O'Connell's widow subdivided and sold off most of the original grant, and a pattern of intersecting streets was laid out, mostly named after famous streets in [[London]] (e.g. Piccadilly Street, Gladstone Parade etc.). A substantial railway station, churches and other infrastructure were also constructed. The presumption was that Riverstone was set to become an important regional centre but this did not actually happen.\n\nMost of the allotments were eventually taken up for suburban housing but a few of the original 1880s blocks remain vacant to the present day. ''Riverstone terrace'', erected in 1883, is a curious relic of the anticipated 19th century population boom. It was meant to be the first of a row of high-density terrace housing units that would run the length of Garfield road. However this single block and the small unit next to it were the only ones ever built. For many years the sight of a high density inner-city housing block situated in an empty country paddock remained a bizarre local landmark.\n\nRiverstone remained a small country town until the beginning of the 21st century when the current housing boom swallowed it up as  part of the [[urban sprawl]]. Large areas of former farmland have recently (2014) also been released for housing in Riverstone and surrounding suburbs.  On its northern side Riverstone still has a large and thriving industrial area.<ref name=\"City of Blacktown website\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blacktown.nsw.gov.au/Discover_Blacktown/Our_History_Heritage/Becoming_a_City/Suburb_Historys/Riverstone |publisher=[[City of Blacktown]] |title=Riverstone |work=Discover Blacktown: Our History & Heritage: Becoming a City: Suburb History's |accessdate=27 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227073851/http://www.blacktown.nsw.gov.au/Discover_Blacktown/Our_History_Heritage/Becoming_a_City/Suburb_Historys/Riverstone |archivedate=27 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Poultry farming and intensive market gardening are also still important activities in the area.\n\n==Population==\nAccording to the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]] of Population, there were 7,247 people in Riverstone.\n* Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people made up 4.5% of the population. \n* 74.3% of people were born in Australia. The next most common countries of birth were India 2.0%, Philippines 1.8%, England 1.8% and New Zealand 1.4%.   \n* 78.2% of people spoke only English at home. Other languages spoken at home included Maltese at 1.5%. \n* The most common responses for religion were  Catholic 29.5%, No Religion 20.7% and Anglican 18.7%.<ref name=abs2016/>\n\n==Schools==\nRiverstone features two public schools: [[Riverstone High School]] and Riverstone Public School. It also has three private schools: St Johns Catholic Primary School (Est 1882), Norwest Christian College<ref>http://www.norwest.nsw.edu.au/</ref> (1980) (formerly known as Coverdale Christian School) and<ref>http://marsdenpark.acc.edu.au/</ref> Australian Christian College. ACC has two components: the on campus day school and the distance education school, which serves home educated students across New South Wales.\n\n==Churches==\n*Riverstone Baptist Church<ref>http://www.riverstonebaptist.org.au/</ref> - corner McCulloch and Regent Streets\n* Riverstone Community Church<ref>http://www.rivochurch.com/</ref> - corner Garfield Road East and Hamilton Street\n* Riverstone Anglican Church (St Pauls)<ref>http://www.riverstone.anglican.asn.au/</ref> - 19 Elizabeth Street\n* Riverstone Uniting Church - corner Oxford Street and Garfield Road East\n* St Johns Catholic Church - corner Garfield Road East and McCulloch Street\n* Voice of Victory Church - Sam Lane Centre, Park Street\n* Free Presbyterian - corner Oxford and Regent Streets\n\n==Transport==\n[[Image:Riverstone level Crossing.jpg|thumb|Level crossing at Riverstone]]\nRiverstone is situated between the Richmond Road running from Blacktown to Richmond, and the Windsor Road running from Windsor to North Parramatta.\n\n[[Riverstone railway station]] is on the Richmond branch of the [[North Shore & Western Line]] on the [[Sydney Trains]] network, between [[Blacktown railway station|Blacktown]] and [[Richmond railway station, Sydney|Richmond]]. From dawn to about 9pm, commuter trains to Sydney leave at approximately 30 minute intervals, in most cases coinciding with the arrival of a train from Sydney. They stay for two minutes because the next station, Vineyard, is single platform. After that they shift to an hourly schedule. Depending on the hour, train services running through Riverstone offer a varying number of \"limited stops\" to the Sydney CBD and the majority then continue over the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] to the North Shore line and Hornsby or Berowra. Apart from the city stations, transfer to most other lines is easily made at Strathfield, Redfern or Parramatta, and other stops that offer fewer choices. The peak-hour journey from Riverstone to Central takes a little over an hour, and another 20 minutes to the popular destination of [[Chatswood, New South Wales|Chatswood]]. Buses at Riverstone are run by Busways with route 757 that goes to Mount Druitt and 747 to Marsden Park and Rouse Hill.\n\nDevelopments at the Garfield Rd traffic lights adjacent to the Railway Station have caused massive traffic disruptions.<ref>http://rouse-hill-times.whereilive.com.au/news/story/outrage-at-riverstone-lights/</ref>\n\nRiverstone is one of the few suburbs left in the Sydney region with a level crossing with old-fashioned boom gates. This view looking west onto the undeveloped flood-prone paddocks is popular with Sydney film and TV commercial makers as a stand-in for a small country railway station. The final parting scene in the film [[Beneath Clouds]] was shot there.\n\nThe [[Westlink M7|M7 Motorway]] can be accessed by the Richmond Road ramp to provide faster access from Riverstone to the City. Riverstone and surrounding suburbs have a continuous motorway link to [[Sydney Airport]] via the [[Lane Cove Tunnel]].\n\nTallawong [[Sydney Metro|Metro]] Station is located just 10 minutes by car from Riverstone's CBD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Riverstone+NSW/Tallawong,+Rouse+Hill+NSW+2155/@-33.6858155,150.8660128,14z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m14!4m13!1m5!1m1!1s0x6b129e3951bc8b71:0x5017d681632c880!2m2!1d150.8594!2d-33.6819!1m5!1m1!1s0x6b129efe3561808d:0xfbf948ad4581d955!2m2!1d150.9060436!2d-33.6916153!3e0|title=Riverstone to Tallawong|website=Riverstone to Tallawong|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\n== National Broadband Network (NBN) ==\nRiverstone was named<ref name=\"Geographical rollout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbn.gov.au/content/geographical-rollout |publisher= Australian Government |title=Geographical rollout of NBN|accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> as one of the second release sites in the rollout of the optical fibre [[National Broadband Network]]. As of March 2014 most of the Riverstone residential streets were fitted with the NBN cable.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{coord|33|40|55|S|150|51|34|E|display=title}}\n{{portal|New South Wales}}\n* http://riverstonehistoricalsociety.org.au/ Riverstone & District Historical Society\n* http://www.users.on.net/~woolwash/examples/index.htm Joseph Henry Cragg's Riverstone 1880-1920\n* http://www.nbn.gov.au/content/geographical-rollout\n\n{{Sydney Blacktown suburbs}}\n{{Hawkesbury suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Sydney]]\n[[Category:Riverstone, New South Wales| ]]\n[[Category:City of Blacktown]]\n[[Category:City of Hawkesbury]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb\n| name     = Riverstone\n| city     = Sydney\n| state    = nsw\n| image    = Riverstonensw.JPG\n| image2   ={{maplink\n|frame=yes\n|frame-width=260\n|frame-height=280\n|frame-align=center\n|zoom=13\n|type=shape\n|stroke-colour=#C60C30\n|stroke-width=3\n}}\n| caption  = Riverstone Town Centre\n| lga      = [[City of Blacktown]], [[City of Hawkesbury]] \n| postcode = 2765\n| est      = \n| pop      = 7247\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=abs2016>{{Census 2016 AUS |id=SSC13368 |name=Riverstone (State Suburb) |accessdate=15 January 2018 |quick=on}}</ref>\n| area     = \n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Riverstone|Riverstone]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Greenway|Greenway]], [[Division of Chifley|Chifley]]\n| near-nw  = [[South Windsor, New South Wales|South Windsor]]\n| near-n   = [[Vineyard, New South Wales|Vineyard]]\n| near-ne  = [[Box Hill, New South Wales|Box Hill]]\n| near-w   = [[Windsor Downs, New South Wales|Windsor Downs]]\n| near-e   = [[Rouse Hill, New South Wales|Rouse Hill]]\n| near-sw  = [[Marsden Park, New South Wales|Marsden Park]]\n| near-s   = [[Schofields, New South Wales|Schofields]]\n| near-se  = [[Rouse Hill, New South Wales|Rouse Hill]]\n| dist1    = 48\n| dir1     = NW\n| location1= Sydney CBD \n}}\n'''Riverstone''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|r|a\u026a|v|'|a\u026a\u0259r|'|s|t|\u0252|n}}) ([[Postcodes in Australia|postcode]]: 2765) is a [[suburb]] of [[Sydney]], in the state of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].<ref>{{NSW GNR|id = ujwGwpqbKW|title = Riverstone|accessdate = 4 August 2013}}</ref>  Riverstone is located {{convert|48|km}} north-west of the [[Sydney central business district]], in the [[City of Blacktown|Blacktown]] and [[City of Hawkesbury|Hawkesbury]] [[Local government in Australia|local government areas]]; parts of the [[Greater Western Sydney]] region. Originally settled in 1803 as part of a government stock farm, Riverstone is one of the oldest towns in Australia.\n\nAs at the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]], Riverstone had an estimated population of 7,247.<ref name=abs2016/>\n\n==History==\nPrior to [[History of Australia (1788-1850)|settlement and colonisation]] of Australia, the area that was to become known as Riverstone was inhabited by the [[Darug people|Darug tribe]]. Most of these people died due to introduced diseases following the arrival of the [[First Fleet]], and the remainder were largely relocated to government farms and a series of settlements.\n\nThe Sydney Cove region originally settled in 1788 turned out to be unsuitable for farming, and after a number of years of near-famine in the colony, efforts were made to relocate food production inland to hopefully more climatically stable regions.  In 1803 a government stock farm was established in what was to become the Riverstone/Marsden Park area, on the basis of the abundant water supply and good grazing land there. In 1810 Lieut-Col [[Maurice Charles O'Connell]] was granted 2,500 acres (10&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land in the district, which he named \"Riverston Farm\", after his birthplace in Ireland. (The \"e\" at the end first appeared on railway timetables in the 1860s, an apparent  misprint that has become the accepted spelling, although the name is still pronounced as though the \"e\" is not present).\n\nOriginally, beef cattle farmed in the area were driven overland to the [[Hawkesbury River]] for transport by sailing ship to the convict settlement at [[Sydney Cove]]. The construction of the Sydney to Richmond Railway line in the 1864 both eliminated the need for this and opened up the region to non-rural development. \nAn important meatworks was established there in 1878, undergoing various stages of rebuilding and expansion until it closed permanently in 1992.\n\nIn 1970, a major fire at the Riverstone Meatworks killed six men, who were attempting to lead the animals to safety.\n\nIn 1988, as part of a Federal Government programme to commemorate the 200th anniversary of European settlement in Australia, a heritage museum was established in the old Masonic hall.\n\n== Heritage listings ==\nRiverstone has a number of heritage-listed sites, including:\n* Riverstone Parade: [[Riverstone railway station]]<ref name=nswshr-1237>{{cite NSW SHR|5012209|Riverstone Railway Station Group and Residence|hr=01237|fn=H08/00175/1, 10/06094|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Developments==\n[[Image:Riverstone terrace.jpg|thumb|Riverstone Terrace]]\n\nIn the 1880s O'Connell's widow subdivided and sold off most of the original grant, and a pattern of intersecting streets was laid out, mostly named after famous streets in [[London]] (e.g. Piccadilly Street, Gladstone Parade etc.). A substantial railway station, churches and other infrastructure were also constructed. The presumption was that Riverstone was set to become an important regional centre but this did not actually happen.\n\nMost of the allotments were eventually taken up for suburban housing but a few of the original 1880s blocks remain vacant to the present day. ''Riverstone terrace'', erected in 1883, is a curious relic of the anticipated 19th century population boom. It was meant to be the first of a row of high-density terrace housing units that would run the length of Garfield road. However this single block and the small unit next to it were the only ones ever built. For many years the sight of a high density inner-city housing block situated in an empty country paddock remained a bizarre local landmark.\n\nRiverstone remained a small country town until the beginning of the 21st century when the current housing boom swallowed it up as  part of the [[urban sprawl]]. Large areas of former farmland have recently (2014) also been released for housing in Riverstone and surrounding suburbs.  On its northern side Riverstone still has a large and thriving industrial area.<ref name=\"City of Blacktown website\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blacktown.nsw.gov.au/Discover_Blacktown/Our_History_Heritage/Becoming_a_City/Suburb_Historys/Riverstone |publisher=[[City of Blacktown]] |title=Riverstone |work=Discover Blacktown: Our History & Heritage: Becoming a City: Suburb History's |accessdate=27 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227073851/http://www.blacktown.nsw.gov.au/Discover_Blacktown/Our_History_Heritage/Becoming_a_City/Suburb_Historys/Riverstone |archivedate=27 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Poultry farming and intensive market gardening are also still important activities in the area.\n\n==Population==\nAccording to the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]] of Population, there were 7,247 people in Riverstone.\n* Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people made up 4.5% of the population. \n* 74.3% of people were born in Australia. The next most common countries of birth were India 2.0%, Philippines 1.8%, England 1.8% and New Zealand 1.4%.   \n* 78.2% of people spoke only English at home. Other languages spoken at home included Maltese at 1.5%. \n* The most common responses for religion were  Catholic 29.5%, No Religion 20.7% and Anglican 18.7%.<ref name=abs2016/>\n\n==Schools==\nRiverstone features two public schools: [[Riverstone High School]] and Riverstone Public School. It also has three private schools: St Johns Catholic Primary School (Est 1882), Norwest Christian College<ref>http://www.norwest.nsw.edu.au/</ref> (1980) (formerly known as Coverdale Christian School) and<ref>http://marsdenpark.acc.edu.au/</ref> Australian Christian College. ACC has two components: the on campus day school and the distance education school, which serves home educated students across New South Wales.\n\n==Churches==\n*Riverstone Baptist Church<ref>http://www.riverstonebaptist.org.au/</ref> - corner McCulloch and Regent Streets\n* Riverstone Community Church<ref>http://www.rivochurch.com/</ref> - corner Garfield Road East and Hamilton Street\n* Riverstone Anglican Church (St Pauls)<ref>http://www.riverstone.anglican.asn.au/</ref> - 19 Elizabeth Street\n* Riverstone Uniting Church - corner Oxford Street and Garfield Road East\n* St Johns Catholic Church - corner Garfield Road East and McCulloch Street\n* Voice of Victory Church - Sam Lane Centre, Park Street\n* Free Presbyterian - corner Oxford and Regent Streets\n\n==Transport==\n[[Image:Riverstone level Crossing.jpg|thumb|Level crossing at Riverstone]]\nRiverstone is situated between the Richmond Road running from Blacktown to Richmond, and the Windsor Road running from Windsor to North Parramatta.\n\n[[Riverstone railway station]] is on the Richmond branch of the [[North Shore & Western Line]] on the [[Sydney Trains]] network, between [[Blacktown railway station|Blacktown]] and [[Richmond railway station, Sydney|Richmond]]. From dawn to about 9pm, commuter trains to Sydney leave at approximately 30 minute intervals, in most cases coinciding with the arrival of a train from Sydney. They stay for two minutes because the next station, Vineyard, is single platform. After that they shift to an hourly schedule. Depending on the hour, train services running through Riverstone offer a varying number of \"limited stops\" to the Sydney CBD and the majority then continue over the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] to the North Shore line and Hornsby or Berowra. Apart from the city stations, transfer to most other lines is easily made at Strathfield, Redfern or Parramatta, and other stops that offer fewer choices. The peak-hour journey from Riverstone to Central takes a little over an hour, and another 20 minutes to the popular destination of [[Chatswood, New South Wales|Chatswood]]. Buses at Riverstone are run by Busways with route 757 that goes to Mount Druitt and 747 to Marsden Park and Rouse Hill.\n\nDevelopments at the Garfield Rd traffic lights adjacent to the Railway Station have caused massive traffic disruptions.<ref>http://rouse-hill-times.whereilive.com.au/news/story/outrage-at-riverstone-lights/</ref>\n\nRiverstone is one of the few suburbs left in the Sydney region with a level crossing with old-fashioned boom gates. This view looking west onto the undeveloped flood-prone paddocks is popular with Sydney film and TV commercial makers as a stand-in for a small country railway station. The final parting scene in the film [[Beneath Clouds]] was shot there.\n\nThe [[Westlink M7|M7 Motorway]] can be accessed by the Richmond Road ramp to provide faster access from Riverstone to the City. Riverstone and surrounding suburbs have a continuous motorway link to [[Sydney Airport]] via the [[Lane Cove Tunnel]].\n\nTallawong [[Sydney Metro|Metro]] Station is located just 10 minutes by car from Riverstone's CBD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Riverstone+NSW/Tallawong,+Rouse+Hill+NSW+2155/@-33.6858155,150.8660128,14z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m14!4m13!1m5!1m1!1s0x6b129e3951bc8b71:0x5017d681632c880!2m2!1d150.8594!2d-33.6819!1m5!1m1!1s0x6b129efe3561808d:0xfbf948ad4581d955!2m2!1d150.9060436!2d-33.6916153!3e0|title=Riverstone to Tallawong|website=Riverstone to Tallawong|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\n== National Broadband Network (NBN) ==\nRiverstone was named<ref name=\"Geographical rollout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbn.gov.au/content/geographical-rollout |publisher= Australian Government |title=Geographical rollout of NBN|accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> as one of the second release sites in the rollout of the optical fibre [[National Broadband Network]]. As of March 2014 most of the Riverstone residential streets were fitted with the NBN cable.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{coord|33|40|55|S|150|51|34|E|display=title}}\n{{portal|New South Wales}}\n* http://riverstonehistoricalsociety.org.au/ Riverstone & District Historical Society\n* http://www.users.on.net/~woolwash/examples/index.htm Joseph Henry Cragg's Riverstone 1880-1920\n* http://www.nbn.gov.au/content/geographical-rollout\n\n{{Sydney Blacktown suburbs}}\n{{Hawkesbury suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Sydney]]\n[[Category:Riverstone, New South Wales| ]]\n[[Category:City of Blacktown]]\n[[Category:City of Hawkesbury]]\n", "name_user": "CasisCute", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHeritage listings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riverstone,_New_South_Wales"}
