{"title_page": "Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry\n|image=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry Cap Badge.jpg\n|caption=Badge of the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry\n|dates=1 July 1881 \u2013 5 October 1959\n|country={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch=[[Image:Flag of the British Army.svg|23px]] [[British Army|Army]]\n|type=[[Line infantry]]\n|role=[[Light infantry]]\n|size= 1\u20132 [[Regular army|Regular]] battalions<br>\n1 [[Militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] and [[Militia (United Kingdom)#The Special Reserve|special reserve]] battalion<br>\n1\u20132 [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|volunteer]] battalions<br>\nUp to 10 hostilities-only battalions\n|garrison=[[Victoria Barracks, Bodmin]]<ref name=dcli1>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_index.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |author= |date=25 September 2008 |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher= |accessdate=4 April 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|ceremonial_chief_label=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment_label=\n|nickname=\n|motto=\n|patron=\n|allegiance=\n|colors_label= \n|colors=White facings\n|march=Quick: ''One and All''\n|mascot= \n|battles=\n|command_structure=\n|notable_commanders= \n|anniversaries=\n}}\n[[File:1st DCLI 2461766468 war cross.jpg|thumb|First DCLI Commonwealth War Graves Commission Cemetery, The Bluff in Belgium]] \nThe '''Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry''' (DCLI) was a [[Light infantry|light]] [[infantry]] [[regiment]] of the [[British Army]] in existence from 1881 to 1959.\n\nThe regiment was created on 1 July 1881 as part of the [[Childers Reforms]], by the merger of the [[32nd (Cornwall) Regiment of Foot|32nd (Cornwall Light Infantry) Regiment of Foot]] and the [[46th (South Devonshire) Regiment of Foot]].  The DCLI also incorporated the [[militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|rifle volunteers]] of [[Cornwall]].\n\nIn 1959 the regiment merged with the [[Somerset Light Infantry|Somerset Light Infantry (Prince Albert's)]] to form the [[Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]]. However, this was amalgamated with the [[Durham Light Infantry]], the [[King's Shropshire Light Infantry]] and the [[King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry]] to form [[The Light Infantry]] which was also merged, in 2007, with the [[Devonshire and Dorset Regiment]], the [[Royal Gloucestershire, Berkshire and Wiltshire Regiment]] and the [[Royal Green Jackets]] to form [[The Rifles]], which continues the lineage of the DCLI.\n\n==History==\nThe regiment was created on 1 July 1881 as part of the [[Childers Reforms]], by the merger of the [[32nd (Cornwall Light Infantry) Regiment of Foot]] and the [[46th (South Devonshire) Regiment of Foot]], which became respectively the 1st Battalion and the 2nd Battalion of The Duke of Cornwall\u2019s Light Infantry.<ref name=lg1881>{{London Gazette|issue=24992|pages=3300\u20133301|date=1 July 1881}}</ref>  The DCLI also incorporated the [[militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|rifle volunteers]] of [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Farmer |first=John S |year=1901 |title=The Regimental Records of the British Army : a historical r\u00e9sum\u00e9 chronologically arranged of titles, campaigns, honours, uniforms, facings, badges, nicknames, etc. |url=https://archive.org/details/regimentalrecord00farm |location=London |publisher=Grant Richards |page=}}{{page needed|date=June 2013}}</ref><ref name=swinson>{{cite book |last=Swinson |first=Arthur |year=1972 |title=A Register of the Regiments and Corps of the British Army |location=London |publisher=The Archive Press |isbn=0-85591-000-3 |page=}}{{page needed|date=June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wickes |first=HL |year=1974 |title=Regiments of Foot: A History of the Foot Regiments of the British Army |location=Reading, Berks. |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=0-85045-220-1 |page=}}{{page needed|date=June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1881&ndash;1899===\nUnder the [[Childers Reforms|Childers system]], one regular battalion of each regiment was to be at a \"home\" station, while the other was abroad. Every few years, there was to be an exchange of battalions. In the period from the regiment's formation to the outbreak of the [[Second Boer War]] the two regular battalions were stationed as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Location of 1st Battalion (ex 32nd Foot)<ref name=1bn>{{cite web |url=http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/032-1.htm|title=1st Bn, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |first=T F |last=Mills |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=3 April 2005 |month= |year= |work=Land Forces of Britain, The Empire and the Commonwealth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221053831/http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/032-1.htm |archivedate=21 December 2007 |accessdate=9 April 2010 }}</ref>\n! Years\n! Location of 2nd Battalion (ex 46th Foot)<ref name=2bn>{{cite web |url=http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/046-1.htm|title=2nd Bn, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |first=T F |last=Mills |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=11 September 2005 |month= |year= |work=Land Forces of Britain, The Empire and the Commonwealth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221233605/http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/046-1.htm |archivedate=21 December 2007 |accessdate=10 April 2010 }}</ref>\n! Years\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|England and Ireland\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1881&ndash;1885\n|Gibraltar\n|1881&ndash;1882\n|-\n|Egypt\n|1882&ndash;1885\n|-\n|[[Malta]]\n|1885&ndash;1888\n|Sudan\n|1885&ndash;1886\n|-\n|India and Burma (fought in [[Tirah Campaign]] of 1897)\n|1888&ndash;1900\n|England and Ireland\n|1886&ndash;1900\n|}\n\n===1899&ndash;1914===\nIn October 1899 war broke out between the United Kingdom and the [[Boer Republics]]. The 2nd Battalion arrived in South Africa in the following month, where it took part in minor actions on the western border of the Cape Colony. In February 1900 it became part of the [[19th Light Brigade (United Kingdom)|19th Brigade]]. It saw action against the Boers at [[Battle of Paardeberg|Paardeberg]], and in March 1900 entered [[Bloemfontein]]. It continued to take part in a series of skirmishes until the end of the war.<ref name=angloboer>{{cite web |url=http://www.angloboerwar.com/units%20imperial/dcli.htm |title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |first=David |last=Biggins |work=Anglo Boer War |accessdate=9 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508143035/http://angloboerwar.com/units%20imperial/dcli.htm |archivedate=8 May 2009 }}</ref> The 1st Battalion took no part on the war, moving from India to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] in December 1900<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence |day_of_week=Saturday |date=29 Dec 1901 |page_number=9 |issue=36338| }}</ref> where its soldiers guarded South African [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]].<ref name=1bn/>\n\nFollowing the war in South Africa, the system of rotating battalions between home and foreign stations resumed as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Location of 1st Battalion (ex 32nd Foot)<ref name=1bn/>\n! Years\n! Location of 2nd Battalion (ex 46th Foot)<ref name=2bn/>\n! Years\n|-\n|South Africa\n|1902&ndash;1906\n|England\n|1902&ndash;1905\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|England\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1906&ndash;1913\n|[[Gibraltar]]\n|1905&ndash;1907\n|-\n|[[Bermuda]]\n|1907&ndash;1910\n|-\n|South Africa\n|1910&ndash;1913\n|-\n|Ireland ([[The Curragh]])\n|1913&ndash;1914\n|[[Hong Kong]]\n|1913&ndash;1914\n|}\n\n====Reserve battalions 1881&ndash;1914====\nThe 1881 reorganisation also redesignated the militia and rifle volunteers of Cornwall as battalions of the regiment as follows:<ref name=litimeline>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_timeline.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |author= |date=2 December 2007 |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher= |accessdate=9 April 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 3rd (Militia) Battalion (formerly the \"Royal Cornwall Rangers, Duke of Cornwall's Own Rifles\", raised 1760)\n* 1st Volunteer Battalion (formerly 1st Cornwall Rifle Volunteer Corps, raised 1860)\n* 2nd Volunteer Battalion (formerly 2nd Cornwall Rifle Volunteer Corps, raised 1860)\n\nNeither militia nor volunteer battalions were liable for service outside the United Kingdom. However, in the Second Boer War, both volunteer battalions contributed \"Active Service Companies\" that reinforced the regular battalions, and were awarded the battle honour \"South Africa 1900&ndash;1901\".<ref name=lita>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_tabattalions.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |author= |date=2 December 2007 |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher= |accessdate=9 April 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1908 reserve forces were reorganised by the [[Haldane Reforms|Territorial and Reserve Forces Act 1907]] (the Haldane Reforms). The militia was renamed the \"Special Reserve\", with the duty of providing trained recruits in time of war. The volunteer battalions became part of the new [[Territorial Force]], which was organised into 14 infantry divisions which were called upon to serve abroad.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dunlop |first=John K |year=1938 |title=The development of the British Army 1899\u20131914 |location=London |publisher=[[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]] |pages=280\u2013285}}</ref> On 1 April 1908 the three reserve battalions were accordingly redesignated as the 3rd (Special Reserve) Battalion at the regimental depot, the 4th (Territorial Force) Battalion at [[New Bridge Street drill hall, Truro|New Bridge Street]] in [[Truro]] and the 5th (Territorial Force) Battalion at [[Honey Street drill hall, Bodmin|Honey Street]] in [[Bodmin]].<ref>Order in Council dated 19 March 1908 {{London Gazette |issue=28121 |date=20 June 1908 |pages=2149\u20132162 }}</ref>\n\n===First World War===\nThe war saw a large expansion of the regiment. This was done in two ways: by the formation of duplicate units to the existing territorial battalions, and by the raising of wartime \"new army\" or \"service\" battalions. The following battalions of the DCLI saw active service in the conflict:<ref name=ww1>{{cite web |url=http://www.1914-1918.net/dcli.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry  |author=Chris Baker |work=The Long, Long Trail |publisher= |accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Battalion\n! Service\n|-\n|1st Battalion\n|[[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] 1914&ndash;1917; [[Italian Campaign (World War I)|Italian Front]] 1917&ndash;1918; Western Front 1918\n|-\n|2nd Battalion\n|Western Front 1914&ndash;1915; [[Macedonian front (World War I)|Macedonian Front]] 1915&ndash;1918\n|-\n|1/4th Battalion\n|India 1914&ndash;1916; Aden 1916&ndash;1917; Egypt 1917&ndash;1918\n|-\n|2/4th Battalion\n|(Formed September 1914) India 1914&ndash;1918\n|-\n|1/5th Battalion\n|Remained in UK until 1916. Western Front 1916&ndash;1918\n|-\n|6th (Service) Battalion\n|(Formed August 1914) Western Front 1915&ndash;1918 (disbanded February 1918)\n|-\n|7th (Service) Battalion\n|(Formed September 1914) Western Front 1915&ndash;1918\n|-\n|8th (Service) Battalion\n|(Formed September 1914) Western Front 1915; Macedonian Front 1915&ndash;1918\n|-\n|10th (Service) Battalion (Cornwall Pioneers)\n| (Formed March 1915) Western Front 1916&ndash;1918\n|}\n\n===Inter-war period===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Years\n! 1st Battalion<ref name=1bn/>\n! Years\n! 2nd Battalion<ref name=2bn/>\n|-\n|1919&ndash;1922\n|Ireland\n|1919&ndash;1920\n|India\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|1922&ndash;1939\n|rowspan=\"8\"|India\n|-\n|1920&ndash;1921\n|[[Iraqi revolt against the British|Iraq]]\n|-\n|1921&ndash;1922\n|[[Irish War of Independence|Ireland]]\n|-\n|1922&ndash;1924\n|Germany (Army of occupation)\n|-\n|1924&ndash;1927\n|Guernsey\n|-\n|1927&ndash;1932\n|England\n|-\n|1932&ndash;1935\n|Gibraltar\n|-\n|1935&ndash;1939\n|England\n|}\n\n[[File:DUKW and Universal Carriers of 5th Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry, 43rd Division, Holland, 18 September 1944. BU934.jpg|thumb|Members of the 5th Battalion during the [[History of the Netherlands (1939\u20131945)#Liberation|Liberation of the Netherlands]], September 1944]]\n\n===Second World War===\nDuring the war the regiment was increased to seven battalions. However, only the 1st, 2nd and 5th served overseas.<ref name=BAF>{{cite web |url=http://www.britisharmedforces.org/li_pages/regiments/dcli/duke_timeline.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130414131644/http://www.britisharmedforces.org/li_pages/regiments/dcli/duke_timeline.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 April 2013 |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher=British Armed Forces.org |date=2 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe 2nd Battalion, DCLI was serving in [[10th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|10th Infantry Brigade]], which also included the 2nd [[Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment]] and 1st [[Queen's Own Royal West Kent Regiment]], part of the [[4th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|4th Infantry Division]], and was sent overseas to France shortly after the outbreak of war, where they arrived on 1 October 1939 as part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] (BEF). The battalion remained in France for many months until May 1940 when the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] [[Battle of the Netherlands|invaded Holland]], [[Battle of Belgium|Belgium]] and [[Battle of France|France]], where they, along with the rest of the BEF, were forced into a [[Battle of Dunkirk|retreat to the Dunkirk perimeter]] where they were subsequently [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuated to England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/duke-cornwalls-light-infantry|title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|publisher=National Army Museum|accessdate=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230233102/http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/duke-cornwalls-light-infantry|archive-date=2015-12-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1944, during the [[Operation Jupiter (1944)|Battle of Hill 112]] (Operation Jupiter), during the [[Battle for Caen]], part of the larger [[Operation Overlord|Battle of Normandy]], the hill acquired the name \"Cornwall Hill\" after Cornish soldiers of 5th Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry, under [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Sir John Carew Pole, 12th Baronet|John Pole]], suffered 320 casualties there. The battalion was part of the [[214th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|214th Infantry Brigade]] attached to the [[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/1060024009|title=The 43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division's 214 Brigade crosses the Seine at Vernon|publisher=Imperial War Museum|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war===\nThe regiment reverted to two battalions following the war.\n\nBetween 1946 and 1954, the 1st Battalion served in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Cyprus]], [[Somaliland]], [[England]], and the [[Federal Republic of Germany]]. The 2nd Battalion, between 1946 and 1948, served in [[Greece]] (including [[East Macedonia and Thrace|Eastern Macedonia]]). In 1948, it was reduced to a skeleton \"representative cadre\", before being amalgamated into the 1st Battalion in 1950.<ref name=BAF/>\n\nIn 1954, the 1st Battalion was posted to [[Jamaica]], the last battalion to be posted to the West Indies for a full, three-year term.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://sites.google.com/site/djkl157/home |work=A Company, 1st Battalion, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |title=Prospect Garrison, Devonshire Bermuda: 1954 - 1957 |date=21 October 2008 |accessdate=}}</ref> ''A'' Company detached on transit, posted to [[Prospect Camp, Bermuda|Prospect Camp]], in the [[Atlantic ocean|Atlantic]] archipelago of [[Bermuda]]. The [[Bermuda Garrison]] no longer received a full regular army infantry battalion, as the part-time [[Bermuda Volunteer Rifle Corps]] (BVRC) (retitled Bermuda Rifles in 1949) and [[Bermuda Militia Artillery]] (BMA) had long-since taken on most of the responsibility for local defence. ''A'' Company was the last regular unit posted on garrison to Bermuda, with its departure constituting the withdrawal of the garrison from the one-time Fortress Bermuda. The officer commanding ''A'' Company, Major J. Anthony Marsh, DSO, a Second World War veteran of the [[Special Air Service]], took permanent residence in Bermuda after leaving the regular army, retiring from military service in 1970 as a lieutenant-colonel, having commanded the Bermuda Militia Artillery and the [[Royal Bermuda Regiment]] (a 1965 amalgam of the BMA and the Bermuda Rifles).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warwickandwarwick.com/pages/library/medals/sasww2.htm |publisher=Warwick & Warwick |title=Outstanding Special Air Service WWII Distinguished Service Order group to Lieutenant Colonel John Anthony Marsh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502005106/http://www.warwickandwarwick.com/pages/library/medals/sasww2.htm |archivedate=2014-05-02 }}</ref> ''E'' Company also detached, being posted to [[Belize|British Honduras]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://limostwanted.wordpress.com/e-company-1dcli-54-57-belize/ |work=Light Infantry Most Wanted |title=E Company 1 DCLI: Belize |publisher=[[WordPress]] |year=2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> In 1957, ''A'' and ''E'' companies reunited with the rest of the battalion in England, before being posted to [[Osnabr\u00fcck]] in Germany, where it remained until 1959.<ref name=BAF/>\n\nOn the 6 October 1959, the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry merged with the [[Somerset Light Infantry]] to form the [[Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]].<ref name=swinson/><ref name=BAF/>\n\n== Cornwall Rifle Volunteers ==\nThe 1st Administrative Battalion, Cornwall Rifle Volunteers was first formed in June of 1960 consisting of 21 Rifle Volunteer Corps or \"Companies\" the last being raised in January of 1861.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-so/co-4.htm|title=4th Battalion, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|date=14 February 2019|website=regiments.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080107125417/http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-so/co-4.htm|archive-date=7 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947 after [[World War 2]] and as part of the demobilization the 4th and 5th battalions merged to create the new 4th/5th Battalion.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lightinfantry.me.uk/dukecornwallli.htm|title=Duke of Cornwalls Light Infantry|website=www.lightinfantry.me.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>  The battalion had the following structure upon formation:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://british-army-units1945on.co.uk/territorial-army-infantry/duke-of-cornwall-s-light-infantry-2.html|title=British Army units from 1945 on - Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|website=british-army-units1945on.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n* Headquarters - [[Truro]]\n** A Company - [[Penzance]]\n** B Company - [[Truro]]\n** C Company - [[Liskeard]]\n** D Company - [[Bodmin]]\n\nIn 1959 after the [[1957 Defence White Paper]] the [[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]] merged with the [[Somerset Light Infantry]] to form the new [[Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_books.htm|title=British Light Infantry Regiments|website=www.lightinfantry.org.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>  In 1960 the battalion was re-named to \"The Duke of Cornwwall's Light Infantry (TA)\".  In 1967 after the reforms to the [[1966 Defence White Paper]] the battalion was disbanded and re-formed as a Territorial Battalion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalcornwallmuseum.org.uk/the-haslam-diaries/duke-of-cornwalls-light-infantry|title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|website=Royal Cornwall Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  The unit had the following:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n* A ([[Cornwall]]) Company, [[Light Infantry Volunteers]] as part of [[TAVR|TAVR II]] - [[Truro]]\n* The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry Territorials as part of [[TAVR|TAVR III]] - [[Truro]]\n* A (Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry) Company - [[Bodmin]]\n* B ([[Cornwall Fortress Royal Engineers|Cornwall Fortress Engineers]]) Company - [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]]\n\nIn 1968 after further changes after the [[1966 Defence White Paper]] all the unit was moved under control of the new larger regiment, [[The Light Infantry]].<ref name=\":0\" />  Later on in 1971 the unit was re-formed and consisted of the following:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n* A ([[Cornwall]]) Company, [[Light Infantry Volunteers]] - [[Truro]]\n* C ([[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]) Company, 6th Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]] - [[Cambourne]]\n* D ([[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]) Company, 6th Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]] - [[Penzance]]\n\nIn 1972 the [[Light Infantry Volunteers]] were re-designated as the 5th Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]].  Later in 1988 the 6th Battalion of [[The Light Infantry]] was re-designated as the 6th ([[Somerset]] and [[Cornwall]]) Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]].  Finally when the [[Strategic Defence Review]] came the D ([[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|Cornwall Light Infantry]]) Company was re-formed as part of the new [[Rifle Volunteers]].  The company still exists as \"D Company\" within the 6th Battalion of [[The Rifles]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/d_company/index.htm|title=D Company|date=14 February 2019|website=army.mod.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108214709/http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/d_company/index.htm|archive-date=8 January 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/about_us/index.htm|title=About us|date=14 February 2019|website=army.mod.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108214654/http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/about_us/index.htm|archive-date=8 January 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dlisouthshields.org.uk/3/1/5/Somerset-and-Cornwall-Light-Infantry|title=Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry - SCLI|website=www.dlisouthshields.org.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Regimental museum==\n[[File:Bodmin Military Museum 01.jpg|DCLI Regimental Museum|thumb]]\nThe Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry regimental collections are displayed at Cornwall's Regimental Museum at [[Victoria Barracks, Bodmin|Victoria Barracks]] in [[Bodmin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armymuseums.org.uk/museum/cornwalls-regimental-museum/|title=Cornwall's Regimental Museum|publisher=Ogilby Trust|accessdate=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143740/https://www.armymuseums.org.uk/museum/cornwalls-regimental-museum/|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[St Petroc's Church, Bodmin]] was the regimental place of worship where there are memorials to some of the servicemen and [[regimental colours]] from the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_chapels.htm|title=Regimental chapels of the DCLI|accessdate=2009-07-26}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Literature==\n''[[Surfing Tommies]]'' is a 2009 play by the Cornish author [[Alan M. Kent]] which follows the lives of three members of the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry on a journey from the mines of Cornwall to the fields of [[Flanders]], where they learned to surf with [[South Africa]]n troops.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/whatson/Hanging-10-trenches/article-947675-detail/article.html |title=Hanging 10 in the trenches |publisher=[[Local World]] |date=29 April 2009 |access-date=20 May 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505080512/http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/whatson/Hanging-10-trenches/article-947675-detail/article.html |archive-date=5 May 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable members==\n[[File:VCThomasEdwardRendle.jpg|thumb|Sergeant Thomas Edward Rendle, VC]]\n\n===Recipients of the Victoria Cross===\n\nEight soldiers of the DCLI were awarded the VC injbjbij/iojolijlkcluding:\n\n* Lieutenant [[Herbert Augustine Carter]]\n* Lieutenant [[Philip Curtis]] (medal displayed in the Museum)\n* [[Thomas Edward Rendle]] (medal displayed in the Museum)\n* [[Clement Leslie Smith]] (medal displayed in the Museum)\n\n===Others===\n*Captain [[Piers Edgcumbe, 5th Earl of Mount Edgcumbe]], served in the South African War \n*Lieutenant-General [[Arthur Floyer-Acland|Arthur Nugent Floyer-Acland]] [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (7 September 1885 &ndash; 18 February 1980)\n*John Moore, a Major of the 32nd regiment who died at the [[Siege of Lucknow]]\n*[[Harry Patch]], a supercentenarian, the last [[Tommy Atkins|Tommy]], served on the Western Front of the Great War. (d. July 2009) Patch was the last male First World War veteran living in Europe and the last British male known to have been born in the 1890s.\n*Harold Royffe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scli.co.uk/pages/harold_royffe.htm |title=Capt. QM Harold Royffe |publisher=Somerset & Cornwall Light Infantry |accessdate=2009-08-09 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*Major-General [[David Tyacke]] (born 1915 at [[Breage, Cornwall]]; d. 2010); Colonel 1957\u201359 (afterwards deputy colonel of the Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry)<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |title=Viewspaper |date=4 May 2010 |page=9}}</ref>\n*Sir [[David Willcocks]] [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Military Cross|MC]], [[choir|choral]] [[conducting|conductor]], [[Organ (music)|organist]], and [[composer]], was formerly an officer in the regiment.\n*  [[Sir Arthur Quiller-Couch]], the Cornish writer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01s2sml|title=Fowey, Cornwall: The Poet Who Raised a Battalion|publisher=BBC|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Battle honours==\n[[Battle honours of the British and Imperial Armies|Battle honours]] of the regiment:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ieeOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=%22Duke+of+Cornwall%27s+Light+Infantry%22+%22Battle+Honours%22&source=bl&ots=CN3mm5PX7d&sig=9OtivBSeuwNYSTMMnZvGE550pkY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9kMGbrf7JAhVFRhQKHX4xBwc4ChDoAQg0MAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Duke%20of%20Cornwall's%20Light%20Infantry%22%20%22Battle%20Honours%22&f=false|title=The Handbook of British Regiments|publisher=Routledge Revivals|first= Christopher |last=Chan|page=143|year=2014|isbn=978-0415710794}}</ref>\n*''From 32nd Regiment of Foot'': Roli\u00e7a, Vimiero, Corunna, Salamanca, Pyrenees, Nivelle, Nive, Orthes, Peninsula, Waterloo, Goojerat, Mooltan, Punjaub, Lucknow \n*''From 46th Regiment of Foot'': Dominica, Sevastopol, Gibraltar 1704-05, Dettingen, St. Lucia 1778, \n*''Early wars'': Tel el Kebir, Egypt 1882, Nile 1884-85, Paardeberg, South Africa 1899-1902,\n*''The Great War (15 battalions)'':  Mons, Le Cateau, Retreat from Mons, Marne 1914, Aisne 1914, La Bass\u00e9e 1914, Armenti8\u00e8res 1914, Ypres 1915 '17, Gravenstafel, St. Julien, Frezenberg, Bellewaarde, Hooge 1915, Mount Sorrel, Somme 1916 '18, Delville Wood, Guillemont, Flers-Courcelette, Morval, Le Transloy, Ancre 1916, Bapaume 1917 '18, Arras 1917, Vimy 1917, Scarpe 1917, Arleux, Langemarck 1917, Menin Road, Polygon Wood, Broodseinde, Poelcappelle, Passchendaele, Cambrai 1917 '18, St. Quentin, Rosi\u00e8res, Lys, Estaires, Hazebrouck, Albert 1918, Hindenburg Line, Havrincourt, Canal du Nord, Selle, Sambre, France and Flanders 1914-18, Italy 1917-18, Struma, Doiran 1917 '18, Macedonia 1915-18, Gaza, Nebi Samwil, Jerusalem, Tell 'Asur, Megiddo, Sharon, Palestine 1917-18, Aden\n*''The Second World War'':  Defence of Escaut, Cheux, Hill 112, Mont Pincon, Noireau Crossing, Nederrijn, Opheusden, Geilenkirchen, Rhineland, Goch, Rhine, North-West Europe 1940 '44-45, Gazala, Medjez Plain, Si Abdallah, North Africa 1942-43, Cassino II, Trasimene Line, Advance to Florence, Incontro, Rimini Line, Italy 1944-45\n\n==List of Colonels of the Regiment==\nColonels of the regiment were as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regiments.org:80/regiments/uk/inf/032DCLI.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118040213/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/032DCLI.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-01-18|title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|publisher=Regiments.org|first=T.F.|last=Mills|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 1881\u20131890 (1st Battalion): General [[William Jones (British Army officer)|Sir William Jones]] (ex [[32nd Foot]])\n* 1881\u20131892 (2nd Battalion): General [[Charles Stuart (British Army officer, born 1810)|Charles Stuart]] (ex [[46th Foot]])\n* 3 April 1890 (1st Battalion only to 1892): General [[John Thomas Hill]]\n* 16 April 1902: Lieutenant-General [[Granville Chetwynd-Stapylton|Granville George Chetwynd Stapylton]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27435|page=3324| date=20 May 1902}}</ref>\n* 28 April 1915: Lieutenant-General [[Reginald Pole-Carew (British Army officer)|Reginald Pole-Carew]]\n* 12 May 1923: Lieutenant-General [[Harold Bridgwood Walker]]\n* 26 April 1932: Brigadier-General Martin Newman Turner\n* 29 June 1935: General [[Walter Venning]] (retired 1942)\n* 17 January 1947: General Sir [[Daril Watson]]\n* 18 October 1953: Major-General [[Vyvyan Evelegh]]\n* 27 August 1958: Major-General [[Robert Goldsmith|Robert Burrell Frederick Kinglake Goldsmith]] \n* ''1959: regiment amalgamated with [[The Somerset Light Infantry (Prince Albert's)]] to form [[The Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]]''\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* [[:Category:Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry officers|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry officers]]\n* [[:Category:Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry soldiers|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry soldiers]]\n*[[First DCLI Commonwealth War Graves Commission Cemetery, The Bluff]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry}}\n*[https://cornwalls-regimentalmuseum.org/ Cornwall's Regimental Museum]\n{{The Rifles}}\n{{British Infantry Regiments World War I}}\n\n[[Category:1881 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British light infantry]]\n[[Category:Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|*]]\n[[Category:Infantry regiments of the British Army|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1881]]\n[[Category:Regiments of the British Army in World War I]]\n[[Category:Regiments of the British Army in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry\n|image=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry Cap Badge.jpg\n|caption=Badge of the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry\n|dates=1 July 1881 \u2013 5 October 1959\n|country={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch=[[Image:Flag of the British Army.svg|23px]] [[British Army|Army]]\n|type=[[Line infantry]]\n|role=[[Light infantry]]\n|size= 1\u20132 [[Regular army|Regular]] battalions<br>\n1 [[Militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] and [[Militia (United Kingdom)#The Special Reserve|special reserve]] battalion<br>\n1\u20132 [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|volunteer]] battalions<br>\nUp to 10 hostilities-only battalions\n|garrison=[[Victoria Barracks, Bodmin]]<ref name=dcli1>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_index.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |author= |date=25 September 2008 |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher= |accessdate=4 April 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|ceremonial_chief_label=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment_label=\n|nickname=\n|motto=\n|patron=\n|allegiance=\n|colors_label= \n|colors=White facings\n|march=Quick: ''One and All''\n|mascot= \n|battles=\n|command_structure=\n|notable_commanders= \n|anniversaries=\n}}\n[[File:1st DCLI 2461766468 war cross.jpg|thumb|First DCLI Commonwealth War Graves Commission Cemetery, The Bluff in Belgium]] \nThe '''Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry''' (DCLI) was a [[Light infantry|light]] [[infantry]] [[regiment]] of the [[British Army]] in existence from 1881 to 1959.\n\nThe regiment was created on 1 July 1881 as part of the [[Childers Reforms]], by the merger of the [[32nd (Cornwall) Regiment of Foot|32nd (Cornwall Light Infantry) Regiment of Foot]] and the [[46th (South Devonshire) Regiment of Foot]].  The DCLI also incorporated the [[militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|rifle volunteers]] of [[Cornwall]].\n\nIn 1959 the regiment merged with the [[Somerset Light Infantry|Somerset Light Infantry (Prince Albert's)]] to form the [[Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]]. However, this was amalgamated with the [[Durham Light Infantry]], the [[King's Shropshire Light Infantry]] and the [[King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry]] to form [[The Light Infantry]] which was also merged, in 2007, with the [[Devonshire and Dorset Regiment]], the [[Royal Gloucestershire, Berkshire and Wiltshire Regiment]] and the [[Royal Green Jackets]] to form [[The Rifles]], which continues the lineage of the DCLI.\n\n==History==\nThe regiment was created on 1 July 1881 as part of the [[Childers Reforms]], by the merger of the [[32nd (Cornwall Light Infantry) Regiment of Foot]] and the [[46th (South Devonshire) Regiment of Foot]], which became respectively the 1st Battalion and the 2nd Battalion of The Duke of Cornwall\u2019s Light Infantry.<ref name=lg1881>{{London Gazette|issue=24992|pages=3300\u20133301|date=1 July 1881}}</ref>  The DCLI also incorporated the [[militia (United Kingdom)|militia]] and [[Volunteer Force (Great Britain)|rifle volunteers]] of [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Farmer |first=John S |year=1901 |title=The Regimental Records of the British Army : a historical r\u00e9sum\u00e9 chronologically arranged of titles, campaigns, honours, uniforms, facings, badges, nicknames, etc. |url=https://archive.org/details/regimentalrecord00farm |location=London |publisher=Grant Richards |page=}}{{page needed|date=June 2013}}</ref><ref name=swinson>{{cite book |last=Swinson |first=Arthur |year=1972 |title=A Register of the Regiments and Corps of the British Army |location=London |publisher=The Archive Press |isbn=0-85591-000-3 |page=}}{{page needed|date=June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wickes |first=HL |year=1974 |title=Regiments of Foot: A History of the Foot Regiments of the British Army |location=Reading, Berks. |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=0-85045-220-1 |page=}}{{page needed|date=June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1881&ndash;1899===\nUnder the [[Childers Reforms|Childers system]], one regular battalion of each regiment was to be at a \"home\" station, while the other was abroad. Every few years, there was to be an exchange of battalions. In the period from the regiment's formation to the outbreak of the [[Second Boer War]] the two regular battalions were stationed as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Location of 1st Battalion (ex 32nd Foot)<ref name=1bn>{{cite web |url=http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/032-1.htm|title=1st Bn, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |first=T F |last=Mills |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=3 April 2005 |month= |year= |work=Land Forces of Britain, The Empire and the Commonwealth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221053831/http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/032-1.htm |archivedate=21 December 2007 |accessdate=9 April 2010 }}</ref>\n! Years\n! Location of 2nd Battalion (ex 46th Foot)<ref name=2bn>{{cite web |url=http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/046-1.htm|title=2nd Bn, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |first=T F |last=Mills |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=11 September 2005 |month= |year= |work=Land Forces of Britain, The Empire and the Commonwealth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221233605/http://www.regiments.org/deploy/uk/reg-inf/046-1.htm |archivedate=21 December 2007 |accessdate=10 April 2010 }}</ref>\n! Years\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|England and Ireland\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1881&ndash;1885\n|Gibraltar\n|1881&ndash;1882\n|-\n|Egypt\n|1882&ndash;1885\n|-\n|[[Malta]]\n|1885&ndash;1888\n|Sudan\n|1885&ndash;1886\n|-\n|India and Burma (fought in [[Tirah Campaign]] of 1897)\n|1888&ndash;1900\n|England and Ireland\n|1886&ndash;1900\n|}\n\n===1899&ndash;1914===\nIn October 1899 war broke out between the United Kingdom and the [[Boer Republics]]. The 2nd Battalion arrived in South Africa in the following month, where it took part in minor actions on the western border of the Cape Colony. In February 1900 it became part of the [[19th Light Brigade (United Kingdom)|19th Brigade]]. It saw action against the Boers at [[Battle of Paardeberg|Paardeberg]], and in March 1900 entered [[Bloemfontein]]. It continued to take part in a series of skirmishes until the end of the war.<ref name=angloboer>{{cite web |url=http://www.angloboerwar.com/units%20imperial/dcli.htm |title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |first=David |last=Biggins |work=Anglo Boer War |accessdate=9 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508143035/http://angloboerwar.com/units%20imperial/dcli.htm |archivedate=8 May 2009 }}</ref> The 1st Battalion took no part on the war, moving from India to [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]] in December 1900<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence |day_of_week=Saturday |date=29 Dec 1901 |page_number=9 |issue=36338| }}</ref> where its soldiers guarded South African [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]].<ref name=1bn/>\n\nFollowing the war in South Africa, the system of rotating battalions between home and foreign stations resumed as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Location of 1st Battalion (ex 32nd Foot)<ref name=1bn/>\n! Years\n! Location of 2nd Battalion (ex 46th Foot)<ref name=2bn/>\n! Years\n|-\n|South Africa\n|1902&ndash;1906\n|England\n|1902&ndash;1905\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|England\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1906&ndash;1913\n|[[Gibraltar]]\n|1905&ndash;1907\n|-\n|[[Bermuda]]\n|1907&ndash;1910\n|-\n|South Africa\n|1910&ndash;1913\n|-\n|Ireland ([[The Curragh]])\n|1913&ndash;1914\n|[[Hong Kong]]\n|1913&ndash;1914\n|}\n\n====Reserve battalions 1881&ndash;1914====\nThe 1881 reorganisation also redesignated the militia and rifle volunteers of Cornwall as battalions of the regiment as follows:<ref name=litimeline>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_timeline.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |author= |date=2 December 2007 |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher= |accessdate=9 April 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 3rd (Militia) Battalion (formerly the \"Royal Cornwall Rangers, Duke of Cornwall's Own Rifles\", raised 1760)\n* 1st Volunteer Battalion (formerly 1st Cornwall Rifle Volunteer Corps, raised 1860)\n* 2nd Volunteer Battalion (formerly 2nd Cornwall Rifle Volunteer Corps, raised 1860)\n\nNeither militia nor volunteer battalions were liable for service outside the United Kingdom. However, in the Second Boer War, both volunteer battalions contributed \"Active Service Companies\" that reinforced the regular battalions, and were awarded the battle honour \"South Africa 1900&ndash;1901\".<ref name=lita>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_tabattalions.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |author= |date=2 December 2007 |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher= |accessdate=9 April 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1908 reserve forces were reorganised by the [[Haldane Reforms|Territorial and Reserve Forces Act 1907]] (the Haldane Reforms). The militia was renamed the \"Special Reserve\", with the duty of providing trained recruits in time of war. The volunteer battalions became part of the new [[Territorial Force]], which was organised into 14 infantry divisions which were called upon to serve abroad.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dunlop |first=John K |year=1938 |title=The development of the British Army 1899\u20131914 |location=London |publisher=[[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]] |pages=280\u2013285}}</ref> On 1 April 1908 the three reserve battalions were accordingly redesignated as the 3rd (Special Reserve) Battalion at the regimental depot, the 4th (Territorial Force) Battalion at [[New Bridge Street drill hall, Truro|New Bridge Street]] in [[Truro]] and the 5th (Territorial Force) Battalion at [[Honey Street drill hall, Bodmin|Honey Street]] in [[Bodmin]].<ref>Order in Council dated 19 March 1908 {{London Gazette |issue=28121 |date=20 June 1908 |pages=2149\u20132162 }}</ref>\n\n===First World War===\nThe war saw a large expansion of the regiment. This was done in two ways: by the formation of duplicate units to the existing territorial battalions, and by the raising of wartime \"new army\" or \"service\" battalions. The following battalions of the DCLI saw active service in the conflict:<ref name=ww1>{{cite web |url=http://www.1914-1918.net/dcli.htm |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry  |author=Chris Baker |work=The Long, Long Trail |publisher= |accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Battalion\n! Service\n|-\n|1st Battalion\n|[[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] 1914&ndash;1917; [[Italian Campaign (World War I)|Italian Front]] 1917&ndash;1918; Western Front 1918\n|-\n|2nd Battalion\n|Western Front 1914&ndash;1915; [[Macedonian front (World War I)|Macedonian Front]] 1915&ndash;1918\n|-\n|1/4th Battalion\n|India 1914&ndash;1916; Aden 1916&ndash;1917; Egypt 1917&ndash;1918\n|-\n|2/4th Battalion\n|(Formed September 1914) India 1914&ndash;1918\n|-\n|1/5th Battalion\n|Remained in UK until 1916. Western Front 1916&ndash;1918\n|-\n|6th (Service) Battalion\n|(Formed August 1914) Western Front 1915&ndash;1918 (disbanded February 1918)\n|-\n|7th (Service) Battalion\n|(Formed September 1914) Western Front 1915&ndash;1918\n|-\n|8th (Service) Battalion\n|(Formed September 1914) Western Front 1915; Macedonian Front 1915&ndash;1918\n|-\n|10th (Service) Battalion (Cornwall Pioneers)\n| (Formed March 1915) Western Front 1916&ndash;1918\n|}\n\n===Inter-war period===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Years\n! 1st Battalion<ref name=1bn/>\n! Years\n! 2nd Battalion<ref name=2bn/>\n|-\n|1919&ndash;1922\n|Ireland\n|1919&ndash;1920\n|India\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|1922&ndash;1939\n|rowspan=\"8\"|India\n|-\n|1920&ndash;1921\n|[[Iraqi revolt against the British|Iraq]]\n|-\n|1921&ndash;1922\n|[[Irish War of Independence|Ireland]]\n|-\n|1922&ndash;1924\n|Germany (Army of occupation)\n|-\n|1924&ndash;1927\n|Guernsey\n|-\n|1927&ndash;1932\n|England\n|-\n|1932&ndash;1935\n|Gibraltar\n|-\n|1935&ndash;1939\n|England\n|}\n\n[[File:DUKW and Universal Carriers of 5th Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry, 43rd Division, Holland, 18 September 1944. BU934.jpg|thumb|Members of the 5th Battalion during the [[History of the Netherlands (1939\u20131945)#Liberation|Liberation of the Netherlands]], September 1944]]\n\n===Second World War===\nDuring the war the regiment was increased to seven battalions. However, only the 1st, 2nd and 5th served overseas.<ref name=BAF>{{cite web |url=http://www.britisharmedforces.org/li_pages/regiments/dcli/duke_timeline.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130414131644/http://www.britisharmedforces.org/li_pages/regiments/dcli/duke_timeline.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 April 2013 |title=The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |work=British Light Infantry Regiments |publisher=British Armed Forces.org |date=2 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe 2nd Battalion, DCLI was serving in [[10th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|10th Infantry Brigade]], which also included the 2nd [[Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment]] and 1st [[Queen's Own Royal West Kent Regiment]], part of the [[4th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|4th Infantry Division]], and was sent overseas to France shortly after the outbreak of war, where they arrived on 1 October 1939 as part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] (BEF). The battalion remained in France for many months until May 1940 when the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] [[Battle of the Netherlands|invaded Holland]], [[Battle of Belgium|Belgium]] and [[Battle of France|France]], where they, along with the rest of the BEF, were forced into a [[Battle of Dunkirk|retreat to the Dunkirk perimeter]] where they were subsequently [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuated to England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/duke-cornwalls-light-infantry|title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|publisher=National Army Museum|accessdate=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230233102/http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/duke-cornwalls-light-infantry|archive-date=2015-12-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1944, during the [[Operation Jupiter (1944)|Battle of Hill 112]] (Operation Jupiter), during the [[Battle for Caen]], part of the larger [[Operation Overlord|Battle of Normandy]], the hill acquired the name \"Cornwall Hill\" after Cornish soldiers of 5th Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry, under [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Sir John Carew Pole, 12th Baronet|John Pole]], suffered 320 casualties there. The battalion was part of the [[214th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|214th Infantry Brigade]] attached to the [[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/1060024009|title=The 43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division's 214 Brigade crosses the Seine at Vernon|publisher=Imperial War Museum|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war===\nThe regiment reverted to two battalions following the war.\n\nBetween 1946 and 1954, the 1st Battalion served in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Cyprus]], [[Somaliland]], [[England]], and the [[Federal Republic of Germany]]. The 2nd Battalion, between 1946 and 1948, served in [[Greece]] (including [[East Macedonia and Thrace|Eastern Macedonia]]). In 1948, it was reduced to a skeleton \"representative cadre\", before being amalgamated into the 1st Battalion in 1950.<ref name=BAF/>\n\nIn 1954, the 1st Battalion was posted to [[Jamaica]], the last battalion to be posted to the West Indies for a full, three-year term.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://sites.google.com/site/djkl157/home |work=A Company, 1st Battalion, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry |title=Prospect Garrison, Devonshire Bermuda: 1954 - 1957 |date=21 October 2008 |accessdate=}}</ref> ''A'' Company detached on transit, posted to [[Prospect Camp, Bermuda|Prospect Camp]], in the [[Atlantic ocean|Atlantic]] archipelago of [[Bermuda]]. The [[Bermuda Garrison]] no longer received a full regular army infantry battalion, as the part-time [[Bermuda Volunteer Rifle Corps]] (BVRC) (retitled Bermuda Rifles in 1949) and [[Bermuda Militia Artillery]] (BMA) had long-since taken on most of the responsibility for local defence. ''A'' Company was the last regular unit posted on garrison to Bermuda, with its departure constituting the withdrawal of the garrison from the one-time Fortress Bermuda. The officer commanding ''A'' Company, Major J. Anthony Marsh, DSO, a Second World War veteran of the [[Special Air Service]], took permanent residence in Bermuda after leaving the regular army, retiring from military service in 1970 as a lieutenant-colonel, having commanded the Bermuda Militia Artillery and the [[Royal Bermuda Regiment]] (a 1965 amalgam of the BMA and the Bermuda Rifles).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warwickandwarwick.com/pages/library/medals/sasww2.htm |publisher=Warwick & Warwick |title=Outstanding Special Air Service WWII Distinguished Service Order group to Lieutenant Colonel John Anthony Marsh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502005106/http://www.warwickandwarwick.com/pages/library/medals/sasww2.htm |archivedate=2014-05-02 }}</ref> ''E'' Company also detached, being posted to [[Belize|British Honduras]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://limostwanted.wordpress.com/e-company-1dcli-54-57-belize/ |work=Light Infantry Most Wanted |title=E Company 1 DCLI: Belize |publisher=[[WordPress]] |year=2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> In 1957, ''A'' and ''E'' companies reunited with the rest of the battalion in England, before being posted to [[Osnabr\u00fcck]] in Germany, where it remained until 1959.<ref name=BAF/>\n\nOn the 6 October 1959, the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry merged with the [[Somerset Light Infantry]] to form the [[Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]].<ref name=swinson/><ref name=BAF/>\n\n== Cornwall Rifle Volunteers ==\nThe 1st Administrative Battalion, Cornwall Rifle Volunteers was first formed in June of 1960 consisting of 21 Rifle Volunteer Corps or \"Companies\" the last being raised in January of 1861.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-so/co-4.htm|title=4th Battalion, The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|date=14 February 2019|website=regiments.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080107125417/http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-so/co-4.htm|archive-date=7 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947 after [[World War 2]] and as part of the demobilization the 4th and 5th battalions merged to create the new 4th/5th Battalion.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lightinfantry.me.uk/dukecornwallli.htm|title=Duke of Cornwalls Light Infantry|website=www.lightinfantry.me.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>  The battalion had the following structure upon formation:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://british-army-units1945on.co.uk/territorial-army-infantry/duke-of-cornwall-s-light-infantry-2.html|title=British Army units from 1945 on - Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|website=british-army-units1945on.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n* Headquarters - [[Truro]]\n** A Company - [[Penzance]]\n** B Company - [[Truro]]\n** C Company - [[Liskeard]]\n** D Company - [[Bodmin]]\n\nIn 1959 after the [[1957 Defence White Paper]] the [[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]] merged with the [[Somerset Light Infantry]] to form the new [[Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_books.htm|title=British Light Infantry Regiments|website=www.lightinfantry.org.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>  In 1960 the battalion was re-named to \"The Duke of Cornwwall's Light Infantry (TA)\".  In 1967 after the reforms to the [[1966 Defence White Paper]] the battalion was disbanded and re-formed as a Territorial Battalion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalcornwallmuseum.org.uk/the-haslam-diaries/duke-of-cornwalls-light-infantry|title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|website=Royal Cornwall Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  The unit had the following:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n* A ([[Cornwall]]) Company, [[Light Infantry Volunteers]] as part of [[TAVR|TAVR II]] - [[Truro]]\n* The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry Territorials as part of [[TAVR|TAVR III]] - [[Truro]]\n* A (Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry) Company - [[Bodmin]]\n* B ([[Cornwall Fortress Royal Engineers|Cornwall Fortress Engineers]]) Company - [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]]\n\nIn 1968 after further changes after the [[1966 Defence White Paper]] all the unit was moved under control of the new larger regiment, [[The Light Infantry]].<ref name=\":0\" />  Later on in 1971 the unit was re-formed and consisted of the following:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n* A ([[Cornwall]]) Company, [[Light Infantry Volunteers]] - [[Truro]]\n* C ([[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]) Company, 6th Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]] - [[Cambourne]]\n* D ([[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]) Company, 6th Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]] - [[Penzance]]\n\nIn 1972 the [[Light Infantry Volunteers]] were re-designated as the 5th Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]].  Later in 1988 the 6th Battalion of [[The Light Infantry]] was re-designated as the 6th ([[Somerset]] and [[Cornwall]]) Battalion, [[The Light Infantry]].  Finally when the [[Strategic Defence Review]] came the D ([[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|Cornwall Light Infantry]]) Company was re-formed as part of the new [[Rifle Volunteers]].  The company still exists as \"D Company\" within the 6th Battalion of [[The Rifles]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/d_company/index.htm|title=D Company|date=14 February 2019|website=army.mod.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108214709/http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/d_company/index.htm|archive-date=8 January 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/about_us/index.htm|title=About us|date=14 February 2019|website=army.mod.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108214654/http://www.army.mod.uk/riflevolunteers/about_us/index.htm|archive-date=8 January 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dlisouthshields.org.uk/3/1/5/Somerset-and-Cornwall-Light-Infantry|title=Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry - SCLI|website=www.dlisouthshields.org.uk|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Regimental museum==\n[[File:Bodmin Military Museum 01.jpg|DCLI Regimental Museum|thumb]]\nThe Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry regimental collections are displayed at Cornwall's Regimental Museum at [[Victoria Barracks, Bodmin|Victoria Barracks]] in [[Bodmin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armymuseums.org.uk/museum/cornwalls-regimental-museum/|title=Cornwall's Regimental Museum|publisher=Ogilby Trust|accessdate=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143740/https://www.armymuseums.org.uk/museum/cornwalls-regimental-museum/|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[St Petroc's Church, Bodmin]] was the regimental place of worship where there are memorials to some of the servicemen and [[regimental colours]] from the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/dcli/duke_chapels.htm|title=Regimental chapels of the DCLI|accessdate=2009-07-26}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Literature==\n''[[Surfing Tommies]]'' is a 2009 play by the Cornish author [[Alan M. Kent]] which follows the lives of three members of the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry on a journey from the mines of Cornwall to the fields of [[Flanders]], where they learned to surf with [[South Africa]]n troops.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/whatson/Hanging-10-trenches/article-947675-detail/article.html |title=Hanging 10 in the trenches |publisher=[[Local World]] |date=29 April 2009 |access-date=20 May 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505080512/http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/whatson/Hanging-10-trenches/article-947675-detail/article.html |archive-date=5 May 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable members==\n[[File:VCThomasEdwardRendle.jpg|thumb|Sergeant Thomas Edward Rendle, VC]]\n\n===Recipients of the Victoria Cross===\n\nEight soldiers of the DCLI were awarded the VC including:\n\n* Lieutenant [[Herbert Augustine Carter]]\n* Lieutenant [[Philip Curtis]] (medal displayed in the Museum)\n* [[Thomas Edward Rendle]] (medal displayed in the Museum)\n* [[Clement Leslie Smith]] (medal displayed in the Museum)\n\n===Others===\n*Captain [[Piers Edgcumbe, 5th Earl of Mount Edgcumbe]], served in the South African War \n*Lieutenant-General [[Arthur Floyer-Acland|Arthur Nugent Floyer-Acland]] [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (7 September 1885 &ndash; 18 February 1980)\n*John Moore, a Major of the 32nd regiment who died at the [[Siege of Lucknow]]\n*[[Harry Patch]], a supercentenarian, the last [[Tommy Atkins|Tommy]], served on the Western Front of the Great War. (d. July 2009) Patch was the last male First World War veteran living in Europe and the last British male known to have been born in the 1890s.\n*Harold Royffe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scli.co.uk/pages/harold_royffe.htm |title=Capt. QM Harold Royffe |publisher=Somerset & Cornwall Light Infantry |accessdate=2009-08-09 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*Major-General [[David Tyacke]] (born 1915 at [[Breage, Cornwall]]; d. 2010); Colonel 1957\u201359 (afterwards deputy colonel of the Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry)<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |title=Viewspaper |date=4 May 2010 |page=9}}</ref>\n*Sir [[David Willcocks]] [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Military Cross|MC]], [[choir|choral]] [[conducting|conductor]], [[Organ (music)|organist]], and [[composer]], was formerly an officer in the regiment.\n*  [[Sir Arthur Quiller-Couch]], the Cornish writer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01s2sml|title=Fowey, Cornwall: The Poet Who Raised a Battalion|publisher=BBC|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Battle honours==\n[[Battle honours of the British and Imperial Armies|Battle honours]] of the regiment:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ieeOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=%22Duke+of+Cornwall%27s+Light+Infantry%22+%22Battle+Honours%22&source=bl&ots=CN3mm5PX7d&sig=9OtivBSeuwNYSTMMnZvGE550pkY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9kMGbrf7JAhVFRhQKHX4xBwc4ChDoAQg0MAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Duke%20of%20Cornwall's%20Light%20Infantry%22%20%22Battle%20Honours%22&f=false|title=The Handbook of British Regiments|publisher=Routledge Revivals|first= Christopher |last=Chan|page=143|year=2014|isbn=978-0415710794}}</ref>\n*''From 32nd Regiment of Foot'': Roli\u00e7a, Vimiero, Corunna, Salamanca, Pyrenees, Nivelle, Nive, Orthes, Peninsula, Waterloo, Goojerat, Mooltan, Punjaub, Lucknow \n*''From 46th Regiment of Foot'': Dominica, Sevastopol, Gibraltar 1704-05, Dettingen, St. Lucia 1778, \n*''Early wars'': Tel el Kebir, Egypt 1882, Nile 1884-85, Paardeberg, South Africa 1899-1902,\n*''The Great War (15 battalions)'':  Mons, Le Cateau, Retreat from Mons, Marne 1914, Aisne 1914, La Bass\u00e9e 1914, Armenti8\u00e8res 1914, Ypres 1915 '17, Gravenstafel, St. Julien, Frezenberg, Bellewaarde, Hooge 1915, Mount Sorrel, Somme 1916 '18, Delville Wood, Guillemont, Flers-Courcelette, Morval, Le Transloy, Ancre 1916, Bapaume 1917 '18, Arras 1917, Vimy 1917, Scarpe 1917, Arleux, Langemarck 1917, Menin Road, Polygon Wood, Broodseinde, Poelcappelle, Passchendaele, Cambrai 1917 '18, St. Quentin, Rosi\u00e8res, Lys, Estaires, Hazebrouck, Albert 1918, Hindenburg Line, Havrincourt, Canal du Nord, Selle, Sambre, France and Flanders 1914-18, Italy 1917-18, Struma, Doiran 1917 '18, Macedonia 1915-18, Gaza, Nebi Samwil, Jerusalem, Tell 'Asur, Megiddo, Sharon, Palestine 1917-18, Aden\n*''The Second World War'':  Defence of Escaut, Cheux, Hill 112, Mont Pincon, Noireau Crossing, Nederrijn, Opheusden, Geilenkirchen, Rhineland, Goch, Rhine, North-West Europe 1940 '44-45, Gazala, Medjez Plain, Si Abdallah, North Africa 1942-43, Cassino II, Trasimene Line, Advance to Florence, Incontro, Rimini Line, Italy 1944-45\n\n==List of Colonels of the Regiment==\nColonels of the regiment were as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regiments.org:80/regiments/uk/inf/032DCLI.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118040213/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/032DCLI.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-01-18|title=Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|publisher=Regiments.org|first=T.F.|last=Mills|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 1881\u20131890 (1st Battalion): General [[William Jones (British Army officer)|Sir William Jones]] (ex [[32nd Foot]])\n* 1881\u20131892 (2nd Battalion): General [[Charles Stuart (British Army officer, born 1810)|Charles Stuart]] (ex [[46th Foot]])\n* 3 April 1890 (1st Battalion only to 1892): General [[John Thomas Hill]]\n* 16 April 1902: Lieutenant-General [[Granville Chetwynd-Stapylton|Granville George Chetwynd Stapylton]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27435|page=3324| date=20 May 1902}}</ref>\n* 28 April 1915: Lieutenant-General [[Reginald Pole-Carew (British Army officer)|Reginald Pole-Carew]]\n* 12 May 1923: Lieutenant-General [[Harold Bridgwood Walker]]\n* 26 April 1932: Brigadier-General Martin Newman Turner\n* 29 June 1935: General [[Walter Venning]] (retired 1942)\n* 17 January 1947: General Sir [[Daril Watson]]\n* 18 October 1953: Major-General [[Vyvyan Evelegh]]\n* 27 August 1958: Major-General [[Robert Goldsmith|Robert Burrell Frederick Kinglake Goldsmith]] \n* ''1959: regiment amalgamated with [[The Somerset Light Infantry (Prince Albert's)]] to form [[The Somerset and Cornwall Light Infantry]]''\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* [[:Category:Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry officers|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry officers]]\n* [[:Category:Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry soldiers|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry soldiers]]\n*[[First DCLI Commonwealth War Graves Commission Cemetery, The Bluff]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry}}\n*[https://cornwalls-regimentalmuseum.org/ Cornwall's Regimental Museum]\n{{The Rifles}}\n{{British Infantry Regiments World War I}}\n\n[[Category:1881 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British light infantry]]\n[[Category:Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry|*]]\n[[Category:Infantry regiments of the British Army|Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1881]]\n[[Category:Regiments of the British Army in World War I]]\n[[Category:Regiments of the British Army in World War II]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:d090:ca00:902:6397:d867:abdd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eRecipients of the Victoria Cross)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duke_of_Cornwall%27s_Light_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name    = Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?\n|image        = Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne cover.jpg\n|director     = Hilal Saral\n|runtime      = 90 min\n|creator      = Vedat T\u00fcrkali\n|writer       = [[Ece Y\u00f6ren\u00e7]]<br />[[Melek Gen\u00e7o\u011flu]]\n|starring     = [[Beren Saat]]<br/>[[Engin Aky\u00fcrek]]<br />[[F\u0131rat \u00c7elik]]<br />[[Musa Uzunlar]]<br />[[Murat Daltaban]]<br />[[Bu\u011fra G\u00fclsoy]]<br />[[Engin \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]]<br />[[Kaan Ta\u015faner]]\n|company      = [[Ay Yap\u0131m]]\n|composer     = [[Toygar I\u015f\u0131kl\u0131]]\n|first_aired  = {{start date|2010|9|16|df=y}}\n|last_aired   = {{end date|2012|6|21|df=y}}\n|country      = Turkey\n|language     = Turkish\n|num_seasons  = 2\n|num_episodes = 80\n|network      = [[Kanal D]]\n|website      = \n|related      = ''[[Kya Qusoor Hai Amala Ka?]]''\n}}\n'''''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?''''' ({{Translation}} What is Fatmag\u00fcl's crime?) is a [[Turkish television drama]] series produced by Ay Yap\u0131m and broadcast on [[Kanal D]]. The series is based on [[Vedat T\u00fcrkali]]'s scenario,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/radikal2/beren-iyi-ama-ille-de-hulya-1025611/ |title=Beren iyi ama ille de H\u00fclya - Radikal 2 Haberleri |publisher=Radikal |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'', which was made into a film in 1986, [[H\u00fclya Av\u015far]] as Fatmag\u00fcl.<ref>[http://blog.milliyet.com.tr/vedat-turkali-bugunleri-daha-onceden-gorseydi--fatmagul-un-dramini-yazar-miydi-/Blog/?BlogNo=266038 Vedat T\u00fcrkali Bug\u00fcnleri Daha \u00d6nceden G\u00f6rseydi, Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Dram\u0131n\u0131 Yazar m\u0131yd\u0131?], ''Milliyet''</ref> The series is written by the duo Ece Y\u00f6ren\u00e7 and Melek Gen\u00e7o\u011flu. The soundtrack was composed and conducted by [[Toygar I\u015f\u0131kl\u0131]].<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/turkish-drama-fatmagul-indian-remake-kya-kasoor-hai-amla-ka-star-plus-4546638/</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nFatmag\u00fcl Ketenci (Beren Saat) is a lower-class dairy-farm girl who lives in the village [[Ild\u0131r]] on the [[Aegean coast]] belonging to the administrative district of [[\u00c7e\u015fme]], in [[Izmir province]], with her too simple brother Rahimi (B\u00fclent Seyran), his son and his wife Muqadas (Esra Dermancioglu) who hates her for no reason. Fatmag\u00fcl plans to marry her childhood love Mustafa (Firat \u00c7elik), who is a fisherman. They are only waiting for Mustafa to earn much money to finish their house construction before marriage. Then there is the Yasaran family, the rich upper-class business men and their political social elites. Yasaran Family is in Izmir for the engagement ceremony of the son of the elder brother Resat Yasaran (Musa Uzunlar) to the daughter of a politician. Selim (Engin \u00d6zt\u00fcrk) is his son and Erdogan (Kaan Tasaner) his nephew. These cousins have a third friend Vural (Bugra G\u00fclsoy) who also belongs to the upper-class. All these three have spent their childhood in Izmir but as the businesses of their fathers grew, they moved to Istanbul. They have a childhood friend in Izmir, whom they meet on yearly basis when they come there for summer vacations. This fourth friend of theirs is the hero - Kerim Ilgaz (Engin Aky\u00fcrek).\n\nKerim Ilgaz is a well-mannered boy, a blacksmith apprentice by profession, who lives with his aunt Meryem Aksoy (Sumru Yavrucuk), known affectionately as \"Ebe Nine\", who is a homeopath. Kerim was orphaned during childhood so Meryem brought him up as her own son. He works as a carpenter in the workshop of his father's friend. Kerim though unlike his rich friends, is over-powered by their presence. He considers himself important with them and hence, enjoys their company.\n\nFatmag\u00fcl is desperate to be married-off to Mustafa, not only because she loves him but also to get rid away from her nagging sister-in-law. Her desire for Mustafa and an independent married life is growing with time as Muqadas's hatred is growing towards her. Except for Mustafa, she has no one to share her feelings with. While in Izmir, Erdogan, Selim, Vural and Kerim see Fatmagul and the three rich tease her as young boys do. Kerim doesn't like this. Then at Selim's engagement, Keirm comes face-to-face with her as she is working their with her sister-in-law. \n\nThe big event of the season is the engagement of Selim, to the politician Turaner Alag\u00f6z's (Aziz Sarvan) daughter Meltem (Seda G\u00fcven). Kerim after attending Selim's engagement, joins his friends for an after-party. All four go for drinking and drug binge near the sea. Mustafa is leaving for a night fish-catch. Fatmag\u00fcl is coming to see him off. She passes from the area where the drunk boys are singing. Kerim sees her and on recognizing her shouts to his friends 'Guys! Its the same girl'!! Then when she tries to run, Kerim gets hold of her while the other three come near her.\n\nThe tragedy occurs. Fatmag\u00fcl is gang-raped. The four boys are shown to be involved in the crime as she faints when Kerim comes on her. The next morning, a traumatized Fatmag\u00fcl is discovered by Ebe Nine while she is picking herbs. The four boys have already left the crime scene. Kerim drops off Selim and Erdogan at their place and himself goes with Vural to his house. Kerim is left deeply disturbed by the event and is even more distressed to know that the girl has been rescued by his mother. The rich boys are confident in the power of their rich fathers and are sure to be saved. As Muqadas approaches the Yasarans threatening of giving their name to the police (as she had found Selim's engagement ring at the rape-scene), with the course of events, the Yasarans save their sons and forcefully marry Kerim to Fatmag\u00fcl. Kerim accepts the blame of solely raping Fatmag\u00fcl for protecting his friends and also because he believes himself to be guilty. Muqadas is their accomplice in all this. Mustafa is hurt primarily because of his fiance' being raped. He burns their house in front of Fatmag\u00fcl but afterwards believes Yasaran\u2019s false stories of Fatmag\u00fcl being involved in Kerim. Fatmag\u00fcl and Kerim's families sell their properties and move to \u0130stanbul to start a new life.\n\nThe story develops in Istanbul. Fatmag\u00fcl hates Kerim. She insults him, abuses him, spits at him, tries to kill him, etc. Kerim is not sure whether he really raped her, as he was drunk and drugged. But Fatmag\u00fcl believes that he did it as his was the last face she saw before fainting. Then Vural who is having little traumas of guilt, tells Kerim what he knows that; Kerim did not rape Fatmagul. In fact, when she laid there, fainted under open sky, he just sat beside her. Kerim tells this to Fatmag\u00fcl. She believes it but it is of no importance for her as she hates him and considers him as much as culprit as the other three. \n\nThings become complicated due to the exploitations of the Ya\u015farans and their unscrupulous lawyer, M\u00fcnir Telci (Murat Daltaban), who wants to protect them, as well as Mustafa, who seeks revenge as he believes that Kerim and Fatmag\u00fcl had an affair from the beginning. As a result, both the Ya\u015farans and Mustafa start harassing Kerim, Fatmag\u00fcl and their relatives. Kerim initially wild and exhausted with Fatmag\u00fcl's behavior, is ready to leave her and divorce her as she desires. But when he is leaving, Kerim realizes that he loves Fatmag\u00fcl, and this was love at first sight. Before leaving he writes a letter to her, telling her to move on in her life and that one day he will come and ask for forgiveness from her.\n\nFatmag\u00fcl reads this letter. Later-on the viewers are shown that this was the moment when Fatmag\u00fcl fell in love with Kerim as his words softened her heart for him and she believed in what he wrote to her. Anyways, Kerim returns and then the year long, tough but with a happy-end path of Kerim and Fatmagul starts. \n\nHowever, even after she has already developed a soft corner for him, Fatmag\u00fcl is in a state of self-denial about her feelings for Kerim and when one day she sees Vural hugging him, she believes him still to be in contact with her rapists, which actually is not the reality. In order to prove his innocence and love for her, Kerim files her rape case and asks the police to arrest him, Vural and the Ya\u015farans, after which Fatmag\u00fcl finally accepts his of being honest with her. Mustafa after knowing the truth asks Fatmag\u00fcl to forgive him, but she rejects him. Things take a turn when the Ya\u015farans start threatening Kerim and Fatmag\u00fcl, trying to quickly finish the case, while also using the greedy and weak Mustafa against them. During the first trial, the Ya\u015farans falsify their testimonies. They also resort to using several bribed witnesses. Vural then is accidentally killed by Mustafa. \n\nIn the second season, Fatmag\u00fcl also confesses her love for Kerim. After the Yasarans forcefully protect Mustafa against Fatmag\u00fcl, he abducts her, stating he loves her more than Kerim and that he regrets leaving her. Kerim eventually rescues his wife and they escape. Mustafa is arrested and imprisoned for his crimes. At the wedding of Kerim and Fatmag\u00fcl, Mustafa intentionally tries to escape from police custody and is therefore, shot to death. Meanwhile, Selim and Erdo\u011fan surreptitiously move to [[Malta]] where they briefly hide from the authorities. However, they are forced to return to Istanbul after Erdo\u011fan engages in a fight at a nightclub and is arrested. \n\nEventually, Fatmag\u00fcl confronts them in court and they are charged for their part in her rape, essentially bringing down the Ya\u015faran empire. The series ends with Fatmag\u00fcl and Kerim expecting their first child. In the final scene, they walk down the street in Izmir holding hands, expressing that their love cannot be shaken despite the difficult challenges they faced and that when a woman is strong like Fatmag\u00fcl and has the support of a strong husband like Kerim, even a crime like 'rape' cannot escape justice.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cleanup|section|date=November 2016|reason=Per [[WP:SLASH]] we do not use slashes when we write articles, because they introduce ambiguities. In the list below there are numerous character names divided by slashes. It is unclear if this means that the actor played multiple roles, or if the names are nicknames, or if the names represent married names, etc. If the actors portrayed multiple roles it might be wiser to present the content ordered by Character instead of Cast, with one character on each bulleted line. Character descriptions should briefly explain who the character is and what role they had in the story, and should also present real-world information, like details about casting and leaving the series if relevant. See [[WP:TVCAST]] for guidance.}}\n\n<br />\n\n*[[Beren Saat]] as Fatmag\u00fcl Ilgaz (n\u00e9e Ketenci) \u2013 A village girl who was later raped by Erdo\u011fan, Selim, and Vural. Was previously engaged to Mustafa. Later marries Kerim. \n*[[Engin Aky\u00fcrek]] as Kerim Ilgaz \u2013 A blacksmith who falls in love with Fatmag\u00fcl, but was later forced to take the blame for her rape. He marries Fatmag\u00fcl to protect her. Later supports her in the fight against her rapists.\n*[[F\u0131rat \u00c7elik]] as Mustafa Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Halide and Emin's son. He was previously engaged to Fatmag\u00fcl, but after the rape, he leaves her. Swore vengeance on the rapists and Kerim. He accidentally kills Vural following a confrontation.\n*[[Kaan Ta\u015faner]] as Erdo\u011fan Ya\u015faran \u2013 Nephew of the wealthy businessman, Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran. He also took part in Fatmag\u00fcl's rape. \n*[[Engin \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]] as Selim Ya\u015faran \u2013 Son of Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran. Also took part in Fatmag\u00fcl's rape.\n*[[Bu\u011fra G\u00fclsoy]] as Vural Naml\u0131 \u2013 Kerim's friend. Also took part in Fatmag\u00fcl's rape. After the rape, he is left with a scattered psyche, and later regrets his actions. He was accidentally killed by Mustafa.\n*[[Musa Uzunlar]] as Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran \u2013 Selim's father, Erdo\u011fan's uncle, and R\u0131fat's brother. He is a wealthy businessman who tries to cover his family's crimes, including the rape of Fatmag\u00fcl. Suffers a stroke late in the series due to stress. \n* Murat Daltaban as M\u00fcnir Telci \u2013 Selim's maternal uncle and is also the Yasaran's family lawyer.\n* Sevtap \u00d6zaltun as Asu(de) / Hacer Ovac\u0131k / Hacer Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Previously worked as a prostitute. She later becomes Mustafa's wife and gives birth to their child. \n* Seda Guven as Meltem Alag\u00f6z / Ya\u015faran \u2013 Selim's ex-wife. After learning of her ex-husband's actions, she becomes an ally to Fatmag\u00fcl.\n* Sumru Yavrucuk as Meryem Aksoy \u2013 Kerim's adoptive mother who raised him. Affectionately known as \"Ebe Nine\" (\"Granny Ebe\")\n* Salih Zeki Yorulmaz as Galip, Kerim's blacksmith teacher. Dies in a car accident.\n* Deniz T\u00fcrkali as Perihan Ya\u015faran / Telci \u2013 Selim's mother, Re\u015fat's wife, M\u00fcnir's sister. Later turns on her husband after learning of his attempts to cover up crimes committed by Selim and Erdo\u011fan Ya\u015faran.\n* Civan Canova as Kadir Pakal\u0131n \u2013 Fatmag\u00fcl's lawyer. A lawyer and a father-figure to Kerim. Eventually falls in love and marries Meryem Aksoy.\n* Esra Dermanc\u0131o\u011flu as Mukaddes Ketenci \u2013 Rahmi's wife and Fatmag\u00fcl's sister-in-law. Used to scheme against Fatmag\u00fcl and the whole family.\n* B\u00fclent Seyran as Rahmi Ketenci \u2013 Fatmag\u00fcl's brother and Mukaddes' husband.\n* Veda Yurtsever \u0130pek as Ender Alag\u00f6z \u2013 Meltem's mother.\n* Aziz Sarvan as Turaner Alag\u00f6z \u2013 Meltem's father. Commits suicide.\n*[[Mehmet Uslu (actor)|Mehmet Uslu]] as R\u0131fat Ya\u015faran \u2013 Erdo\u011fan's father. Dies from a heart attack. His son blames Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran for his death. \n* Servet Pandur as Leman Naml\u0131 \u2013 Vural's mother. After her son and her husband die, she commits suicide.\n* Z\u00fcht\u00fc Erkan as \u015eemsi Naml\u0131 \u2013 Vural's father. Killed in a car accident.\n* Sacide Ta\u015faner as Halide Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Mustafa's mother. Dies of illness.\n* Toygun Ate\u015f as Emin Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Mustafa's father. Dies of a heart attack.\n* Deniz Bayta\u015f as Hilmiye Ya\u015faran \u2013 Erdo\u011fan's mother.\n* Alper Saylik as Sami Khaner \u2013 A taxi driver and Asu's pimp, though later becomes her friend. He eventually falls in love with her.\n* Alper Kut as \u00d6mer Akari \u2013 Kerim's lawyer and Kadir's friend.\n* Emre Yetim as Emre \u2013 Kerim's and Fatmag\u00fcl's friend. In love with Deniz.\n* G\u00f6zde Kocao\u011flu as Deniz Ilgaz \u2013 Kerim's half-Turkish, half-Australian sister born from his biological father.\n* Nilay Kaya as Gaye \u2013 Meltem's cousin, Erdo\u011fan and M\u00fcnir's love interest\n* Clare Frost as Kristen Norton \u2013 An Englishwoman and Kerim's ex-fianc\u00e9e; still in love with Kerim. After Kerim marries Fatmagul, she leaves him.\n* Ata Y\u0131lmaz \u00d6nal as Murat Ketenci \u2013 Mukaddes' son; Rahmi's adaptive son\n* Ali Yigit as Salih Mercanli \u2013 Murat's biological father. Was previously in love with Mukaddes\n* Beng\u00fc Ergin as Dr. Nil Y\u00f6rgen \u2013 Erdo\u011fan's love interest. Later becomes an ally to Fatmag\u00fcl.\n\n==Series overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n!  Season !! Number of episodes !! Episodes !! Season premiere !! Season finale !! Time of broadcasting ([[Eastern European Time|EET]]) !! TV season !! TV channel\n|-\n| 1 || 39 || 1-39 || 16 September 2010 || 16 June 2011 || 20:00 || 2010-2011 || [[Kanal D]]\n|-\n| 2 || 41 || 40-80 || 8 September 2011 || 21 June 2012 || 21:00 || 2011-2012 || [[Kanal D]]\n|}\n==International broadcasts==\nFatmag\u00fcl gained a lot of popularity in [[Turkey]], [[Bangladesh]], [[Pakistan]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Iran]], and the [[Arabic countries]]. It also dubbed in many languages notably [[Persian language|Persian]].\n* {{Flag|Bangladesh}} on [[Deepto TV]] with the title '' \u09ab\u09be\u09a4\u09ae\u09be\u0997\u09c1\u09b2 '' (Fatmagul) \n* {{Flag|India}} on [[Zindagi (TV channel)|Zee Zindagi]] with the title of ''Fatima gul Aakhir Mera Qasoor Kya?'' (Fatma gul - After all what is my fault?)\n* {{Flag|Pakistan}} on [[Urdu 1]] with the title of ''\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u06c1 \u06af\u0644 - \u0622\u062e\u0631 \u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0627 \u0642\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u06a9\u06cc\u0627\u061f'' (Fatma gul - After all what is my fault?)\n* {{Flag|Albania}} on [[Albanian Screen]] with the title ''Fatmagyl''\n* {{Flag|Bosnia}} on [[BHT1 (Bosnia)|BHT1]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast''\n* {{Flag|Israel}} on [[viva (Israel)|Viva]] with the title ''\u05e4\u05d8\u05de\u05d2\u05d5\u05dc'' (Fatmagul)\n* {{Flagicon|Arab League}} [[Arab World]] on [[MBC 1 (Middle East)|MBC1]] With the title ''\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629'' (Fatma)\n* {{flag|Egypt}} \\ {{Flagicon|Arab League}} [[Arab World]]  on CBC with the title ''\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629'' (Fatma)\n* {{Flag|Afghanistan}} on [[Tolo TV]] with the title ''Fatima Gul''\n* {{Flag|Bulgaria}} on [[BTV (Bulgaria)|BTV,BTV Lady]] with the title ''\u041f\u0435\u043f\u0435\u043b \u043e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u0437\u0438'' ''(in English: Ashes of Roses)''\n* {{Flag|Croatia}} on [[Nova TV (Croatia)|Nova TV]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast'' (Lost Honor)\n* {{Flag|Serbia}} on [[Prva Srpska Televizija|Prva TV]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast'' (Lost Honor)\n* {{Flag|Montenegro}} on [[TV Vijesti]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast'' (Lost Honor)\n* {{Flag|France}} on [[TV5Monde]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Georgia}} on Imedi TV with the title ''\u10e3\u10d3\u10d0\u10dc\u10d0\u10e8\u10d0\u10e3\u10da\u10dd''\n* {{Flag|Greece}} on [[Mega Channel]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Kosovo}} on RTV21 with the title ''Fatmagyl''\n* {{Flag|Iran}} on GEM/River with the title ''FatmaGul''\n* {{flag|Lebanon}} on [[Lebanese Broadcasting Corporation|LBCI]] with the title ''Fatma''\n* {{Flag|Spain}} on [[TVE 2]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Russia}} on [[STS (TV channel)|STS]]'' \"\u0411\u0435\u0437 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0432\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430\u044f\"'' (Guilty Without Guilt)\n* {{Flag|England}} on [[Turkish Dramas]] with the title \"What is Fatmagul's Fault?\"\n* {{Flag|Indonesia}} on [[VISION 2 DRAMA INDOVISION]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{flag|Morocco}} on medi 1 With the title \u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629 (Fatma)\n* {{Flag|Macedonia}} on [[Sitel TV]] with the title ''\u0421\u0443\u0434\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0424\u0430\u0442\u043c\u0430\u0453\u0443\u043b'' (Fatmagul destiny)\n* {{Flag|Estonia}} on [[Kanal 2]] with the title ''S\u00fc\u00fctu s\u00fc\u00fcdlane'' (Innocent Culprit)\n* {{Flag|Ukraine}} on [[1+1 (channel)|1+1]] ''\"\u0423 \u0447\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0424\u0430\u0442\u043c\u0430\u0433\u044e\u043b\u044c?\"'' (Where is Fatmagul fault?)\n* {{Flag|Slovakia}} on [[TV Doma]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Lithuania}} on [[LNK (television station)|LNK]] with the title ''Be kalt\u0117s kalta'' (Guilty Without Guilt)\n* {{Flag|Chile}} on [[Mega (Chilean television channel)|Mega]] with the title ''\u00bfQu\u00e9 culpa tiene Fatmag\u00fcl?'' (What is Fatmagul's Fault?)\n* {{Flag|Slovenia}} on [[POP TV]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Peru}} on [[Frecuencia Latina]] with the title ''\u00bfQu\u00e9 culpa tiene Fatmag\u00fcl?'' (What is Fatmagul's Fault?)\n\n==Reception==\n===Iran and Afghanistan===\nTurkish television drama is extremely popular in Iran, where they are dubbed into [[Persian language|Persian]]. Among the most popular series are  ''Fatmagul'', ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'' and ''[[Ezel (TV series)|Ezel]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iranian officials failing to stop of Turkish TV series|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/iranian-officials-failing-to-stop-of-turkish-tv-series.aspx?pageID=238&nID=6171&NewsCatID=385|publisher=Hurriyetdailynews|accessdate=September 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe most popular Turkish show is ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dizifilm.com/haberdetay.asp?newsid=214724|title=Beren Saat Afgan Kad\u0131nlar\u0131n\u0131 Uyar\u0131yor|accessdate=September 15, 2015|work=Dizisifilm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926023209/http://www.dizifilm.com/haberdetay.asp?newsid=214724|archive-date=26 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Another series as ''[[\u00d6yle Bir Ge\u00e7er Zaman Ki]]'' (''As Time Goes By''), ''[[Beni Affet]]'' (''Forgive Me''), ''[[Effet]]'', ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'' (''Forbidden Love''), and [[Ad\u0131n\u0131 Feriha Koydum]] are popular too.\n\n===Balkans and Southeastern Europe===\nIn [[Kosovo]], the most popular TV shows in December 2012 were ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'' (''What is Fatmag\u00fcl's Fault?''), which ranked top of all programmes and ''[[A\u015fk ve Ceza]]'' (''Love and Punishment''), which came in third according to data by [[Index Kosova]]. In [[Serbia]], research from January 2013 indicates that the top two Turkish shows in TV were ''[[Muhte\u015fem Y\u00fczy\u0131l]]'', which ranked fourth, and ''[[\u00d6yle Bir Ge\u00e7er Zaman Ki]]'' (''As Time Goes By''), which came in seventh.<ref name=\"Balkan Insights\">{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/turks-bewitch-the-balkans-with-their-addictive-soaps |title=Turks bewitch the Balkans with their addictive soaps |publisher=Balkan Insights |date= |accessdate=2013-05-03}}</ref> Fatmagul was one of the most popular shows in Macedonia which irked the government to passed a bill to restrict broadcasts of Turkish series during the day and at prime time in order to reduce the Turkish impact on Macedonian society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/macedonia-bans-turkish-soap-operas.aspx?pageID=238&nid=34636 |title=Macedonia bans Turkish soap operas |publisher=Hurriyet Daily News |date= |accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\nThe [[Bengali language|Bangla]] dubbed version of Fatmagul started on [[Deepto TV]] from 2 June 2019 , Saturday to Friday, on 6:30pm and 9:30pm.  Deepto TV  broadcast the finale of the hit [[Bengali language|Bangla]]-dubbed series which aired at 6pm and 9:30pm on Monday, 23 December, 2019. This series became one of the most popular Turkish series in Bangladesh.\n<ref>https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/06/01/fatmagul-and-sultan-suleiman-to-start-from-june-2</ref>\n<ref>https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/09/09/deepto-tv-to-air-100th-episode-of-fatmagul-on-monday</ref>\n<ref>https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/12/22/fatmagul-comes-to-an-end</ref>\n\n===Ethiopia===\n\nFatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne? was well received by Ethiopians due to the popularity of other Turkish dramas that had been previously shown in Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/arts-culture/2016/11/14/ethiopia-takes-delight-in-watching-turkish-drama-series|title=Ethiopia takes delight in watching Turkish drama series|work=DailySabah|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne? was dubbed in Amharic with title \"\u1245\u1323\u1275\" or \"kitat\" and aired on [[Kana TV]].\n\n===Pakistan===\nFatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne? was the second most popular Turkish series in Pakistan which was ranked top in 2013 above Pakistani shows like ''[[Zindagi Gulzar Hai]]'', ''[[Kankar]]'' and ''[[Aunn Zara]]''.<ref name=\"gonnabecrazyforyou.blogspot.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gonnabecrazyforyou.blogspot.com/2014/01/top-six-turkish-dramas-dubbed-in-urdu.html |title=It's fun to be young: Top Six Turkish Dramas (dubbed in Urdu) |publisher=Gonnabecrazyforyou.blogspot.com |date=2014-01-10 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> The series averaged 16% TV ratings with the viewership above 25 million in Pakistani urban and rural market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medialogic.com.pk/tam/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Medialogic_Annual_Review_2013.pdf |format=PDF |title=Television Viewership Overview 2013|website=Medialogic.com.pk |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'', was the highest rated Turkish series which broke all records in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/internacional/noticias/20100630/53955061316/turquia-suena-con-el-amor-prohibido-turquia-ankara-bosforo-estambul-anatolia.html |title=Internacional |website=Lavanguardia.com |date=2015-10-14 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Kimmelman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/18/arts/18abroad.html?nytmobile=0 |title=Soap Operas in the Arab World Yield Their Own Soft Power |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hafsa Khawaja |url=https://hafsakhawaja.wordpress.com/2013/03/16/pakistan-hit-by-fever-of-turkeys-popular-cultural-export/ |title=Pakistan Hit by Fever of Turkey\u2019s Popular Cultural Export \u00ab Hafsa Khawaja's Blog |publisher=Hafsakhawaja.wordpress.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===Arab world===\nIn 2013, the most popular Turkish shows worldwide were ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'', ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'' and ''[[Muhte\u015fem Y\u00fczy\u0131l]]''.<ref name=\"gnctso\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/features/challenge-of-the-turkish-soap-operas-1.1002249 |title=Challenge of the Turkish soap operas |publisher=GulfNews.com |date=2012-04-01 |accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailynewsegypt.com/2013/01/10/turkeys-soap-operas-touch-egypts-heart/ |title=Turkey's soap operas touch Egypt's heart |publisher=Daily News Egypt |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref> ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'' has increased the popularity of Istanbul as a tourist destination among Arabs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thenational.ae/news/world/europe/fatmagul-lures-arab-tourists |title=Fatmagul lures Arab tourists &#124; The National |website=M.thenational.ae |date=2013-04-29 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> With ''A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu's'' popularity ''[[Beren Saat]]'' became the female sensation in Arab television which led to a generally higher viewership for Fatmagul.\n\n===Chile===\n''Binbir Gece'' and ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'' remain the two most watched Turkish shows in [[Chile]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/entretencion/2014/12/661-610748-9-rating-2014-el-ano-que-privilegio-a-mega.shtml|title=Rating 2014: El a\u00f1o que privilegi\u00f3 a Mega|accessdate=September 15, 2015|work=latercera}} {{cite web|url=http://www.fotech.cl/kara-para-ask-nueva-turca-de-mega-baja-su-rating/2015/05/20/|title=\"Kara Para A\u015fk\": Nueva turca de Mega baja su rating|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=Fotech}} \n{{cite web|url=http://www.cambio21.cl/cambio21/site/artic/20150608/pags/20150608170900.html|title=\u00bfEl principio del fin de las telenovelas turcas? Rotundo \u00e9xito del final de \"Fatmag\u00fcl\" no se estar\u00eda dando en las otras producciones en pantalla|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=cambio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925110623/http://www.cambio21.cl/cambio21/site/artic/20150608/pags/20150608170900.html|archive-date=25 September 2015|url-status=dead}}\n{{cite web|url=http://trome.pe/fiesta/fatmagul-supero-al-fondo-hay-sitio-rating-2062567|title=Fatmag\u00fcl super\u00f3 a 'Al fondo hay sitio' en el rating|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=Trome.pe}}\n{{cite web|url=http://www.republica.com.uy/novelas-turcas/525770/|title=Las novelas turcas lideran el rating en Uruguay|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=republica.com.uy}}</ref>\n\n==International remake==\nIn India the show has been remade by Indian TV channel [[Star Plus]] in [[Hindi]] under the title of ''[[Kya Kasoor Hai Amla Ka|Kya Qusoor Hai Amala Ka?]]''. This is the first official remake of the series. The show aired from 3 April 2017 during the noon slot.<ref name=Amla>http://ecchorights.com/press-releases/100</ref><ref name=remake>{{cite news|first=Priyanka|last=Sharma|title=Turkish drama Fatmagul set for an Indian remake titled Kya Kasoor Hai Amla Ka|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/turkish-drama-fatmagul-indian-remake-kya-kasoor-hai-amla-ka-star-plus-4546638/|accessdate=27 February 2017|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> The show features [[Pankhuri Awasthy]] as Amala (Fatmagul), Anant Joshi as Dev (Mustafa) and Rajveer Singh as Abeer (Kerim).<ref name=Amla/> The original show titled ''Fatmagul'' first aired on [[Zindagi TV]] and became a rating success and thus the remake was commissioned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Turkish-stars-all-set-to-shine-in-India/articleshow/52681060.cms|title=Turkish stars all set to shine in India|publisher=Times Of India|work=TNN|date=June 9, 2016| accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"remake\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fatmagulunsucune.tv/ Official site]\n*[http://www.kanald.com.tr/fatmagulunsucune  Kanal D series page]\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1783916/ Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne (2010) ]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fatmagul'un Sucu Ne}}\n[[Category:2010 Turkish television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2012 Turkish television series endings]]\n[[Category:Turkish drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Ay Yap\u0131m]]\n[[Category:2010s Turkish television series]]\n[[Category:Kanal D shows]]\n[[Category:Rape in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name    = Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?\n|image        = Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne cover.jpg\n|director     = Hilal Saral\n|runtime      = 90 min\n|creator      = Vedat T\u00fcrkali\n|writer       = [[Ece Y\u00f6ren\u00e7]]<br />[[Melek Gen\u00e7o\u011flu]]\n|starring     = [[Beren Saat]]<br/>[[Engin Aky\u00fcrek]]<br />[[F\u0131rat \u00c7elik]]<br />[[Musa Uzunlar]]<br />[[Murat Daltaban]]<br />[[Bu\u011fra G\u00fclsoy]]<br />[[Engin \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]]<br />[[Kaan Ta\u015faner]]\n|company      = [[Ay Yap\u0131m]]\n|composer     = [[Toygar I\u015f\u0131kl\u0131]]\n|first_aired  = {{start date|2010|9|16|df=y}}\n|last_aired   = {{end date|2012|6|21|df=y}}\n|country      = Turkey\n|language     = Turkish\n|num_seasons  = 2\n|num_episodes = 80\n|network      = [[Kanal D]]\n|website      = \n|related      = ''[[Kya Qusoor Hai Amala Ka?]]''\n}}\n'''''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?''''' ({{Translation}} What is Fatmag\u00fcl's crime?) is a [[Turkish television drama]] series produced by Ay Yap\u0131m and broadcast on [[Kanal D]]. The series is based on [[Vedat T\u00fcrkali]]'s scenario,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/radikal2/beren-iyi-ama-ille-de-hulya-1025611/ |title=Beren iyi ama ille de H\u00fclya - Radikal 2 Haberleri |publisher=Radikal |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'', which was made into a film in 1986, [[H\u00fclya Av\u015far]] as Fatmag\u00fcl.<ref>[http://blog.milliyet.com.tr/vedat-turkali-bugunleri-daha-onceden-gorseydi--fatmagul-un-dramini-yazar-miydi-/Blog/?BlogNo=266038 Vedat T\u00fcrkali Bug\u00fcnleri Daha \u00d6nceden G\u00f6rseydi, Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Dram\u0131n\u0131 Yazar m\u0131yd\u0131?], ''Milliyet''</ref> The series is written by the duo Ece Y\u00f6ren\u00e7 and Melek Gen\u00e7o\u011flu. The soundtrack was composed and conducted by [[Toygar I\u015f\u0131kl\u0131]].<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/turkish-drama-fatmagul-indian-remake-kya-kasoor-hai-amla-ka-star-plus-4546638/</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nFatmag\u00fcl Ketenci (Beren Saat) is a lower-class dairy-farm girl who lives in the village [[Ild\u0131r]] on the [[Aegean coast]] belonging to the administrative district of [[\u00c7e\u015fme]], in [[Izmir province]], with her too simple brother Rahimi (B\u00fclent Seyran), his son and his wife Muqadas (Esra Dermancioglu) who hates her for no reason. Fatmag\u00fcl plans to marry her childhood love Mustafa (Firat \u00c7elik), who is a fisherman. They are only waiting for Mustafa to earn much money to finish their house construction before marriage. Then there is the Yasaran family, the rich upper-class business men and their political social elites. Yasaran Family is in Izmir for the engagement ceremony of the son of the elder brother Resat Yasaran (Musa Uzunlar) to the daughter of a politician. Selim (Engin \u00d6zt\u00fcrk) is his son and Erdogan (Kaan Tasaner) his nephew. These cousins have a third friend Vural (Bugra G\u00fclsoy) who also belongs to the upper-class. All these three have spent their childhood in Izmir but as the businesses of their fathers grew, they moved to Istanbul. They have a childhood friend in Izmir, whom they meet on yearly basis when they come there for summer vacations. This fourth friend of theirs is the hero - Kerim Ilgaz (Engin Aky\u00fcrek).\n\nKerim Ilgaz is a well-mannered boy, a blacksmith apprentice by profession, who lives with his aunt Meryem Aksoy (Sumru Yavrucuk), known affectionately as \"Ebe Nine\", who is a homeopath. Kerim was orphaned during childhood so Meryem brought him up as her own son. He works as a carpenter in the workshop of his father's friend. Kerim though unlike his rich friends, is over-powered by their presence. He considers himself important with them and hence, enjoys their company.\n\nFatmag\u00fcl is desperate to be married-off to Mustafa, not only because she loves him but also to get rid away from her nagging sister-in-law. Her desire for Mustafa and an independent married life is growing with time as Muqadas's hatred is growing towards her. Except for Mustafa, she has no one to share her feelings with. While in Izmir, Erdogan, Selim, Vural and Kerim see Fatmagul and the three rich tease her as young boys do. Kerim doesn't like this. Then at Selim's engagement, Keirm comes face-to-face with her as she is working their with her sister-in-law. \n\nThe big event of the season is the engagement of Selim, to the politician Turaner Alag\u00f6z's (Aziz Sarvan) daughter Meltem (Seda G\u00fcven). Kerim after attending Selim's engagement, joins his friends for an after-party. All four go for drinking and drug binge near the sea. Mustafa is leaving for a night fish-catch. Fatmag\u00fcl is coming to see him off. She passes from the area where the drunk boys are singing. Kerim sees her and on recognizing her shouts to his friends 'Guys! Its the same girl'!! Then when she tries to run, Kerim gets hold of her while the other three come near her.\n\nThe tragedy occurs. Fatmag\u00fcl is gang-raped. The four boys are shown to be involved in the crime as she faints when Kerim comes on her. The next morning, a traumatized Fatmag\u00fcl is discovered by Ebe Nine while she is picking herbs. The four boys have already left the crime scene. Kerim drops off Selim and Erdogan at their place and himself goes with Vural to his house. Kerim is left deeply disturbed by the event and is even more distressed to know that the girl has been rescued by his mother. The rich boys are confident in the power of their rich fathers and are sure to be saved. As Muqadas approaches the Yasarans threatening of giving their name to the police (as she had found Selim's engagement ring at the rape-scene), with the course of events, the Yasarans save their sons and forcefully marry Kerim to Fatmag\u00fcl. Kerim accepts the blame of solely raping Fatmag\u00fcl for protecting his friends and also because he believes himself to be guilty. Muqadas is their accomplice in all this. Mustafa is hurt primarily because of his fiance' being raped. He burns their house in front of Fatmag\u00fcl but afterwards believes Yasaran\u2019s false stories of Fatmag\u00fcl being involved in Kerim. Fatmag\u00fcl and Kerim's families sell their properties and move to \u0130stanbul to start a new life.\n\nThe story develops in Istanbul. Fatmag\u00fcl hates Kerim. She insults him, abuses him, spits at him, tries to kill him, etc. Kerim is not sure whether he really raped her, as he was drunk and drugged. But Fatmag\u00fcl believes that he did it as his was the last face she saw before fainting. Then Vural who is having little traumas of guilt, tells Kerim what he knows that; Kerim did not rape Fatmagul. In fact, when she laid there, fainted under open sky, he just sat beside her. Kerim tells this to Fatmag\u00fcl. She believes it but it is of no importance for her as she hates him and considers him as much as culprit as the other three. \n\nThings become complicated due to the exploitations of the Ya\u015farans and their unscrupulous lawyer, M\u00fcnir Telci (Murat Daltaban), who wants to protect them, as well as Mustafa, who seeks revenge as he believes that Kerim and Fatmag\u00fcl had an affair from the beginning. As a result, both the Ya\u015farans and Mustafa start harassing Kerim, Fatmag\u00fcl and their relatives. Kerim initially wild and exhausted with Fatmag\u00fcl's behavior, is ready to leave her and divorce her as she desires. But when he is leaving, Kerim realizes that he loves Fatmag\u00fcl, and this was love at first sight. Before leaving he writes a letter to her, telling her to move on in her life and that one day he will come and ask for forgiveness from her.\n\nFatmag\u00fcl reads this letter. Later-on the viewers are shown that this was the moment when Fatmag\u00fcl fell in love with Kerim as his words softened her heart for him and she believed in what he wrote to her. Anyways, Kerim returns and then the year long, tough but with a happy-end path of Kerim and Fatmagul starts. \n\nHowever, even after she has already developed a soft corner for him, Fatmag\u00fcl is in a state of self-denial about her feelings for Kerim and when one day she sees Vural hugging him, she believes him still to be in contact with her rapists, which actually is not the reality. In order to prove his innocence and love for her, Kerim files her rape case and asks the police to arrest him, Vural and the Ya\u015farans, after which Fatmag\u00fcl finally accepts his of being honest with her. Mustafa after knowing the truth asks Fatmag\u00fcl to forgive him, but she rejects him. Things take a turn when the Ya\u015farans start threatening Kerim and Fatmag\u00fcl, trying to quickly finish the case, while also using the greedy and weak Mustafa against them. During the first trial, the Ya\u015farans falsify their testimonies. They also resort to using several bribed witnesses. Vural then is accidentally killed by Mustafa. \n\nIn the second season, Fatmag\u00fcl also confesses her love for Kerim. After the Yasarans forcefully protect Mustafa against Fatmag\u00fcl, he abducts her, stating he loves her more than Kerim and that he regrets leaving her. Kerim eventually rescues his wife and they escape. Mustafa is arrested and imprisoned for his crimes. At the wedding of Kerim and Fatmag\u00fcl, Mustafa intentionally tries to escape from police custody and is therefore, shot to death. Meanwhile, Selim and Erdo\u011fan surreptitiously move to [[Malta]] where they briefly hide from the authorities. However, they are forced to return to Istanbul after Erdo\u011fan engages in a fight at a nightclub and is arrested. \n\nEventually, Fatmag\u00fcl confronts them in court and they are charged for their part in her rape, essentially bringing down the Ya\u015faran empire. The series ends with Fatmag\u00fcl and Kerim expecting their first child. In the final scene, they walk down the street in Izmir holding hands, expressing that their love cannot be shaken despite the difficult challenges they faced and that when a woman is strong like Fatmag\u00fcl and has the support of a strong husband like Kerim, even a crime like 'rape' cannot escape justice.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cleanup|section|date=November 2016|reason=Per [[WP:SLASH]] we do not use slashes when we write articles, because they introduce ambiguities. In the list below there are numerous character names divided by slashes. It is unclear if this means that the actor played multiple roles, or if the names are nicknames, or if the names represent married names, etc. If the actors portrayed multiple roles it might be wiser to present the content ordered by Character instead of Cast, with one character on each bulleted line. Character descriptions should briefly explain who the character is and what role they had in the story, and should also present real-world information, like details about casting and leaving the series if relevant. See [[WP:TVCAST]] for guidance.}}\n\n<br />\n\n*[[Beren Saat]] as Fatmag\u00fcl Ilgaz (n\u00e9e Ketenci) \u2013 A village girl who was later raped by Erdo\u011fan, Selim, and Vural. Was previously engaged to Mustafa. Later marries Kerim. \n*[[Engin Aky\u00fcrek]] as Kerim Ilgaz \u2013 A blacksmith who falls in love with Fatmag\u00fcl, but was later forced to take the blame for her rape. He marries Fatmag\u00fcl to protect her. Later supports her in the fight against her rapists.\n*[[F\u0131rat \u00c7elik]] as Mustafa Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Halide and Emin's son. He was previously engaged to Fatmag\u00fcl, but after the rape, he leaves her. Swore vengeance on the rapists and Kerim. He accidentally kills Vural following a confrontation.\n*[[Kaan Ta\u015faner]] as Erdo\u011fan Ya\u015faran \u2013 Nephew of the wealthy businessman, Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran. He also took part in Fatmag\u00fcl's rape. \n*[[Engin \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]] as Selim Ya\u015faran \u2013 Son of Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran. Also took part in Fatmag\u00fcl's rape.\n*[[Bu\u011fra G\u00fclsoy]] as Vural Naml\u0131 \u2013 Kerim's friend. Also took part in Fatmag\u00fcl's rape. After the rape, he is left with a scattered psyche, and later regrets his actions. He was accidentally killed by Mustafa.\n*[[Musa Uzunlar]] as Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran \u2013 Selim's father, Erdo\u011fan's uncle, and R\u0131fat's brother. He is a wealthy businessman who tries to cover his family's crimes, including the rape of Fatmag\u00fcl. Suffers a stroke late in the series due to stress. \n* Murat Daltaban as M\u00fcnir Telci \u2013 Selim's maternal uncle and is also the Yasaran's family lawyer.\n* Sevtap \u00d6zaltun as Asu(de) / Hacer Ovac\u0131k / Hacer Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Previously worked as a prostitute. She later becomes Mustafa's wife and gives birth to their child. \n* Seda Guven as Meltem Alag\u00f6z / Ya\u015faran \u2013 Selim's ex-wife. After learning of her ex-husband's actions, she becomes an ally to Fatmag\u00fcl.\n* Sumru Yavrucuk as Meryem Aksoy \u2013 Kerim's adoptive mother who raised him. Affectionately known as \"Ebe Nine\" (\"Granny Ebe\")\n* Salih Zeki Yorulmaz as Galip, Kerim's blacksmith teacher. Dies in a car accident.\n* Deniz T\u00fcrkali as Perihan Ya\u015faran / Telci \u2013 Selim's mother, Re\u015fat's wife, M\u00fcnir's sister. Later turns on her husband after learning of his attempts to cover up crimes committed by Selim and Erdo\u011fan Ya\u015faran.\n* Civan Canova as Kadir Pakal\u0131n \u2013 Fatmag\u00fcl's lawyer. A lawyer and a father-figure to Kerim. Eventually falls in love and marries Meryem Aksoy.\n* Esra Dermanc\u0131o\u011flu as Mukaddes Ketenci \u2013 Rahmi's wife and Fatmag\u00fcl's sister-in-law. Used to scheme against Fatmag\u00fcl and the whole family.\n* B\u00fclent Seyran as Rahmi Ketenci \u2013 Fatmag\u00fcl's brother and Mukaddes' husband.\n* Veda Yurtsever \u0130pek as Ender Alag\u00f6z \u2013 Meltem's mother.\n* Aziz Sarvan as Turaner Alag\u00f6z \u2013 Meltem's father. Commits suicide.\n*[[Mehmet Uslu (actor)|Mehmet Uslu]] as R\u0131fat Ya\u015faran \u2013 Erdo\u011fan's father. Dies from a heart attack. His son blames Re\u015fat Ya\u015faran for his death. \n* Servet Pandur as Leman Naml\u0131 \u2013 Vural's mother. After her son and her husband die, she commits suicide.\n* Z\u00fcht\u00fc Erkan as \u015eemsi Naml\u0131 \u2013 Vural's father. Killed in a car accident.\n* Sacide Ta\u015faner as Halide Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Mustafa's mother. Dies of illness.\n* Toygun Ate\u015f as Emin Nal\u00e7al\u0131 \u2013 Mustafa's father. Dies of a heart attack.\n* Deniz Bayta\u015f as Hilmiye Ya\u015faran \u2013 Erdo\u011fan's mother.\n* Alper Saylik as Sami Khaner \u2013 A taxi driver and Asu's pimp, though later becomes her friend. He eventually falls in love with her.\n* Alper Kut as \u00d6mer Akari \u2013 Kerim's lawyer and Kadir's friend.\n* Emre Yetim as Emre \u2013 Kerim's and Fatmag\u00fcl's friend. In love with Deniz.\n* G\u00f6zde Kocao\u011flu as Deniz Ilgaz \u2013 Kerim's half-Turkish, half-Australian sister born from his biological father.\n* Nilay Kaya as Gaye \u2013 Meltem's cousin, Erdo\u011fan and M\u00fcnir's love interest\n* Clare Frost as Kristen Norton \u2013 An Englishwoman and Kerim's ex-fianc\u00e9e; still in love with Kerim. After Kerim marries Fatmagul, she leaves him.\n* Ata Y\u0131lmaz \u00d6nal as Murat Ketenci \u2013 Mukaddes' son; Rahmi's adaptive son\n* Ali Yigit as Salih Mercanli \u2013 Murat's biological father. Was previously in love with Mukaddes\n* Beng\u00fc Ergin as Dr. Nil Y\u00f6rgen \u2013 Erdo\u011fan's love interest. Later becomes an ally to Fatmag\u00fcl.\n\n==Series overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n!  Season !! Number of episodes !! Episodes !! Season premiere !! Season finale !! Time of broadcasting ([[Eastern European Time|EET]]) !! TV season !! TV channel\n|-\n| 1 || 39 || 1-39 || 16 September 2010 || 16 June 2011 || 20:00 || 2010-2011 || [[Kanal D]]\n|-\n| 2 || 41 || 40-80 || 8 September 2011 || 21 June 2012 || 21:00 || 2011-2012 || [[Kanal D]]\n|}\n==International broadcasts==\nFatmag\u00fcl gained a lot of popularity in [[Turkey]], [[Bangladesh]], [[Pakistan]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Iran]], and the [[Arabic countries]]. It also dubbed in many languages notably [[Persian language|Persian]].\n* {{Flag|Bangladesh}} on [[Deepto TV]] with the title '' \u09ab\u09be\u09a4\u09ae\u09be\u0997\u09c1\u09b2 '' (Fatmagul) \n* {{Flag|India}} on [[Zindagi (TV channel)|Zee Zindagi]] with the title of ''Fatima gul Aakhir Mera Qasoor Kya?'' (Fatma gul - After all what is my fault?)\n* {{Flag|Pakistan}} on [[Urdu 1]] with the title of ''\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u06c1 \u06af\u0644 - \u0622\u062e\u0631 \u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0627 \u0642\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u06a9\u06cc\u0627\u061f'' (Fatma gul - After all what is my fault?)\n* {{Flag|Albania}} on [[Albanian Screen]] with the title ''Fatmagyl''\n* {{Flag|Bosnia}} on [[BHT1 (Bosnia)|BHT1]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast''\n* {{Flag|Israel}} on [[viva (Israel)|Viva]] with the title ''\u05e4\u05d8\u05de\u05d2\u05d5\u05dc'' (Fatmagul)\n* {{Flagicon|Arab League}} [[Arab World]] on [[MBC 1 (Middle East)|MBC1]] With the title ''\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629'' (Fatma)\n* {{flag|Egypt}} \\ {{Flagicon|Arab League}} [[Arab World]]  on CBC with the title ''\u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629'' (Fatma)\n* {{Flag|Afghanistan}} on [[Tolo TV]] with the title ''Fatima Gul''\n* {{Flag|Bulgaria}} on [[BTV (Bulgaria)|BTV,BTV Lady]] with the title ''\u041f\u0435\u043f\u0435\u043b \u043e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u0437\u0438'' ''(in English: Ashes of Roses)''\n* {{Flag|Croatia}} on [[Nova TV (Croatia)|Nova TV]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast'' (Lost Honor)\n* {{Flag|Serbia}} on [[Prva Srpska Televizija|Prva TV]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast'' (Lost Honor)\n* {{Flag|Montenegro}} on [[TV Vijesti]] with the title ''Izgubljena \u010dast'' (Lost Honor)\n* {{Flag|France}} on [[TV5Monde]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Georgia}} on Imedi TV with the title ''\u10e3\u10d3\u10d0\u10dc\u10d0\u10e8\u10d0\u10e3\u10da\u10dd''\n* {{Flag|Greece}} on [[Mega Channel]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Kosovo}} on RTV21 with the title ''Fatmagyl''\n* {{Flag|Iran}} on GEM/River with the title ''FatmaGul''\n* {{flag|Lebanon}} on [[Lebanese Broadcasting Corporation|LBCI]] with the title ''Fatma''\n* {{Flag|Spain}} on [[TVE 2]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Russia}} on [[STS (TV channel)|STS]]'' \"\u0411\u0435\u0437 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0432\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430\u044f\"'' (Guilty Without Guilt)\n* {{Flag|England}} on [[Turkish Dramas]] with the title \"What is Fatmagul's Fault?\"\n* {{Flag|Indonesia}} on [[VISION 2 DRAMA INDOVISION]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{flag|Morocco}} on medi 1 With the title \u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u0629 (Fatma)\n* {{Flag|Macedonia}} on [[Sitel TV]] with the title ''\u0421\u0443\u0434\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0424\u0430\u0442\u043c\u0430\u0453\u0443\u043b'' (Fatmagul destiny)\n* {{Flag|Estonia}} on [[Kanal 2]] with the title ''S\u00fc\u00fctu s\u00fc\u00fcdlane'' (Innocent Culprit)\n* {{Flag|Ukraine}} on [[1+1 (channel)|1+1]] ''\"\u0423 \u0447\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0424\u0430\u0442\u043c\u0430\u0433\u044e\u043b\u044c?\"'' (Where is Fatmagul fault?)\n* {{Flag|Slovakia}} on [[TV Doma]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Lithuania}} on [[LNK (television station)|LNK]] with the title ''Be kalt\u0117s kalta'' (Guilty Without Guilt)\n* {{Flag|Chile}} on [[Mega (Chilean television channel)|Mega]] with the title ''\u00bfQu\u00e9 culpa tiene Fatmag\u00fcl?'' (What is Fatmagul's Fault?)\n* {{Flag|Slovenia}} on [[POP TV]] with the title ''Fatmagul''\n* {{Flag|Peru}} on [[Frecuencia Latina]] with the title ''\u00bfQu\u00e9 culpa tiene Fatmag\u00fcl?'' (What is Fatmagul's Fault?)\n\n==Reception==\n===Iran and Afghanistan===\nTurkish television drama is extremely popular in Iran, where they are dubbed into [[Persian language|Persian]]. Among the most popular series are  ''Fatmagul'', ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'' and ''[[Ezel (TV series)|Ezel]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iranian officials failing to stop of Turkish TV series|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/iranian-officials-failing-to-stop-of-turkish-tv-series.aspx?pageID=238&nID=6171&NewsCatID=385|publisher=Hurriyetdailynews|accessdate=September 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe most popular Turkish show is ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dizifilm.com/haberdetay.asp?newsid=214724|title=Beren Saat Afgan Kad\u0131nlar\u0131n\u0131 Uyar\u0131yor|accessdate=September 15, 2015|work=Dizisifilm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926023209/http://www.dizifilm.com/haberdetay.asp?newsid=214724|archive-date=26 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Another series as ''[[\u00d6yle Bir Ge\u00e7er Zaman Ki]]'' (''As Time Goes By''), ''[[Beni Affet]]'' (''Forgive Me''), ''[[Effet]]'', ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'' (''Forbidden Love''), and [[Ad\u0131n\u0131 Feriha Koydum]] are popular too.\n\n===Balkans and Southeastern Europe===\nIn [[Kosovo]], the most popular TV shows in December 2012 were ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'' (''What is Fatmag\u00fcl's Fault?''), which ranked top of all programmes and ''[[A\u015fk ve Ceza]]'' (''Love and Punishment''), which came in third according to data by [[Index Kosova]]. In [[Serbia]], research from January 2013 indicates that the top two Turkish shows in TV were ''[[Muhte\u015fem Y\u00fczy\u0131l]]'', which ranked fourth, and ''[[\u00d6yle Bir Ge\u00e7er Zaman Ki]]'' (''As Time Goes By''), which came in seventh.<ref name=\"Balkan Insights\">{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/turks-bewitch-the-balkans-with-their-addictive-soaps |title=Turks bewitch the Balkans with their addictive soaps |publisher=Balkan Insights |date= |accessdate=2013-05-03}}</ref> Fatmagul was one of the most popular shows in Macedonia which irked the government to passed a bill to restrict broadcasts of Turkish series during the day and at prime time in order to reduce the Turkish impact on Macedonian society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/macedonia-bans-turkish-soap-operas.aspx?pageID=238&nid=34636 |title=Macedonia bans Turkish soap operas |publisher=Hurriyet Daily News |date= |accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\nThe [[Bengali language|Bangla]] dubbed version of Fatmagul started on [[Deepto TV]] from June 2, 2019 , Saturday to Friday, on 6:30pm and 9:30pm.  Deepto TV  broadcasted the finale of the hit [[Bengali language|Bangla]]-dubbed series which aired at 6pm and 9:30pm on Monday, 23rd of December, 2019. This series became one of the most popular Turkish series in Bangladesh.\n<ref>https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/06/01/fatmagul-and-sultan-suleiman-to-start-from-june-2</ref>\n<ref>https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/09/09/deepto-tv-to-air-100th-episode-of-fatmagul-on-monday</ref>\n<ref>https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/12/22/fatmagul-comes-to-an-end</ref>\n\n===Ethiopia===\n\nFatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne? was well received by Ethiopians due to the popularity of other Turkish dramas that had been previously shown in Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/arts-culture/2016/11/14/ethiopia-takes-delight-in-watching-turkish-drama-series|title=Ethiopia takes delight in watching Turkish drama series|work=DailySabah|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne? was dubbed in Amharic with title \"\u1245\u1323\u1275\" or \"kitat\" and aired on [[Kana TV]].\n\n===Pakistan===\nFatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne? was the second most popular Turkish series in Pakistan which was ranked top in 2013 above Pakistani shows like ''[[Zindagi Gulzar Hai]]'', ''[[Kankar]]'' and ''[[Aunn Zara]]''.<ref name=\"gonnabecrazyforyou.blogspot.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gonnabecrazyforyou.blogspot.com/2014/01/top-six-turkish-dramas-dubbed-in-urdu.html |title=It's fun to be young: Top Six Turkish Dramas (dubbed in Urdu) |publisher=Gonnabecrazyforyou.blogspot.com |date=2014-01-10 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> The series averaged 16% TV ratings with the viewership above 25 million in Pakistani urban and rural market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medialogic.com.pk/tam/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Medialogic_Annual_Review_2013.pdf |format=PDF |title=Television Viewership Overview 2013|website=Medialogic.com.pk |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'', was the highest rated Turkish series which broke all records in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/internacional/noticias/20100630/53955061316/turquia-suena-con-el-amor-prohibido-turquia-ankara-bosforo-estambul-anatolia.html |title=Internacional |website=Lavanguardia.com |date=2015-10-14 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Kimmelman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/18/arts/18abroad.html?nytmobile=0 |title=Soap Operas in the Arab World Yield Their Own Soft Power |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hafsa Khawaja |url=https://hafsakhawaja.wordpress.com/2013/03/16/pakistan-hit-by-fever-of-turkeys-popular-cultural-export/ |title=Pakistan Hit by Fever of Turkey\u2019s Popular Cultural Export \u00ab Hafsa Khawaja's Blog |publisher=Hafsakhawaja.wordpress.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===Arab world===\nIn 2013, the most popular Turkish shows worldwide were ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'', ''[[A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu (2008 TV series)|A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu]]'' and ''[[Muhte\u015fem Y\u00fczy\u0131l]]''.<ref name=\"gnctso\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/features/challenge-of-the-turkish-soap-operas-1.1002249 |title=Challenge of the Turkish soap operas |publisher=GulfNews.com |date=2012-04-01 |accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailynewsegypt.com/2013/01/10/turkeys-soap-operas-touch-egypts-heart/ |title=Turkey's soap operas touch Egypt's heart |publisher=Daily News Egypt |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref> ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'' has increased the popularity of Istanbul as a tourist destination among Arabs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thenational.ae/news/world/europe/fatmagul-lures-arab-tourists |title=Fatmagul lures Arab tourists &#124; The National |website=M.thenational.ae |date=2013-04-29 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> With ''A\u015fk-\u0131 Memnu's'' popularity ''[[Beren Saat]]'' became the female sensation in Arab television which led to a generally higher viewership for Fatmagul.\n\n===Chile===\n''Binbir Gece'' and ''Fatmag\u00fcl'\u00fcn Su\u00e7u Ne?'' remain the two most watched Turkish shows in [[Chile]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/entretencion/2014/12/661-610748-9-rating-2014-el-ano-que-privilegio-a-mega.shtml|title=Rating 2014: El a\u00f1o que privilegi\u00f3 a Mega|accessdate=September 15, 2015|work=latercera}} {{cite web|url=http://www.fotech.cl/kara-para-ask-nueva-turca-de-mega-baja-su-rating/2015/05/20/|title=\"Kara Para A\u015fk\": Nueva turca de Mega baja su rating|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=Fotech}} \n{{cite web|url=http://www.cambio21.cl/cambio21/site/artic/20150608/pags/20150608170900.html|title=\u00bfEl principio del fin de las telenovelas turcas? Rotundo \u00e9xito del final de \"Fatmag\u00fcl\" no se estar\u00eda dando en las otras producciones en pantalla|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=cambio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925110623/http://www.cambio21.cl/cambio21/site/artic/20150608/pags/20150608170900.html|archive-date=25 September 2015|url-status=dead}}\n{{cite web|url=http://trome.pe/fiesta/fatmagul-supero-al-fondo-hay-sitio-rating-2062567|title=Fatmag\u00fcl super\u00f3 a 'Al fondo hay sitio' en el rating|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=Trome.pe}}\n{{cite web|url=http://www.republica.com.uy/novelas-turcas/525770/|title=Las novelas turcas lideran el rating en Uruguay|accessdate=September 16, 2015|work=republica.com.uy}}</ref>\n\n==International remake==\nIn India the show has been remade by Indian TV channel [[Star Plus]] in [[Hindi]] under the title of ''[[Kya Kasoor Hai Amla Ka|Kya Qusoor Hai Amala Ka?]]''. This is the first official remake of the series. The show aired from 3 April 2017 during the noon slot.<ref name=Amla>http://ecchorights.com/press-releases/100</ref><ref name=remake>{{cite news|first=Priyanka|last=Sharma|title=Turkish drama Fatmagul set for an Indian remake titled Kya Kasoor Hai Amla Ka|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/television/turkish-drama-fatmagul-indian-remake-kya-kasoor-hai-amla-ka-star-plus-4546638/|accessdate=27 February 2017|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> The show features [[Pankhuri Awasthy]] as Amala (Fatmagul), Anant Joshi as Dev (Mustafa) and Rajveer Singh as Abeer (Kerim).<ref name=Amla/> The original show titled ''Fatmagul'' first aired on [[Zindagi TV]] and became a rating success and thus the remake was commissioned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Turkish-stars-all-set-to-shine-in-India/articleshow/52681060.cms|title=Turkish stars all set to shine in India|publisher=Times Of India|work=TNN|date=June 9, 2016| accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"remake\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fatmagulunsucune.tv/ Official site]\n*[http://www.kanald.com.tr/fatmagulunsucune  Kanal D series page]\n*[https://